animal.description:
Meet Ebony! Ebony had a pretty rough start to life. She was found living in an old SUV in the dead of winter. She was terrified, cold and hungry. She has not had any socialization so everything is new and scary. Ebony has come a long way since she arrived at the shelter, but she is still pretty skittish, and frightened of things. Despite his rough start to life, she is a happy girl! She is friendly, and loves to play. It took awhile for her to even figure out how to play with a toy. Ebony will require a family who can be patient with her and give her the time and space she needs until she feels comfortable. She does not do well with other female dogs, and we aren't sure about male dogs, so we recommend home without any other dogs. She absolutely does NOT like cats. That we know for certain. So she needs to be in a home without cats. We recommend children over 13, as she gets startled easily.

You can visit Ebony at the Euclid Animal Shelter, 25100 Lakeland Blvd., Euclid, OH. He has received his initial set of vaccinations except rabies and will be neutered before leaving the shelter. His adoption fee is $80. All of our dog kennels have indoor/outdoor runs so we cannot say with certainty if any of our dogs are housetrained.

We do not test our animals with other cats or dogs. You are welcome to bring your dog to the shelter for a “Meet and Greet” in one of our outdoor play yards, one of our experienced volunteers will help you.

*** IMPORTANT UPDATE PER OUR ANIMAL CONTROL OFFICER ***

“The Shelter will be changing some policies regarding adoptions and reclaims. Your Health as well as ours here at the Shelter is very important. We will be implementing all of the Health Department’s recommendations.
Reclaims and adoptions will be by appointment only.
You are asked to call the Shelter if you see a dog or cat on line you are interested in or your animal has been impounded.
216-289-2057
Thank You
Ann Mills
Animal Control”

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Mabel ! Here is what would work best for me in my new home:

-Personality: Active, boisterous, a little timid at first
-Can Live with Kids: Mabel is still very much a puppy and doesn't quite realize her size-- she will very easily knock down small children. At this time, we are recommending no kids under 10 years of age, pending an introduction here at the shelter.
-Can Live with Cats: NO- Mabel's previous owner said "SHE HATES CATS" and also "CHASES ANYTHING THAT MOVES".
-Can Live with Dogs: Yes! Another active, rowdy dog of similar size would be great for her!
-Can do Apartment Living: NO- this high energy dog needs a large place to call her own. Ideally she would have access to a securely fenced yard.
-Potty Trained: Appears to be!
-Bite History: No
-Positive Reward Based Obedience Classes Required: Yes-- depending on adopter experience, between 1-3 private lessons.
-Energy Level: Very high!
-Needs Medical Procedure Before Going Home: Yes, a spay
-Additional Information: Mabel is a friendly young dog who was surrendered to the shelter when her owners realized that dogs are a lot of work! Mabel is a rambunctious pup who wasn't given many tools for success in her previous home, but she is super smart, attentive, and eager to learn! While she may be a bit "ruff" around the edges, we know that Mabel has a ton of potential to be an awesome lifelong companion for the right family. Her ideal home has the time, resources, and sense of humor to continue her training.

animal.description:
Hello everyone! My name is Bella! I am a sweet chiweenie girl! I am submissive, easy going, and a total lover! I love to just be with my human! I am great with other animals as you can see! I have foster sibling puppies that are big and little! I am as cute and sweet as it gets! I am around 2-3 years old and I am about 12 pounds. I am completely house and crate trained. I’m still learning to love men but I’m doing so much better. 

The adoption donation fee is $350 which is tax-deductible and goes towards the care of homeless pets with Pals for Paws. 

To expedite the adoption process you can fill out an application online at www.palsforpawsinc.com/adopt. Please note the adoption application doesn’t bind you to anything. Pals for Paws reserves the right to refuse any adoption application for any reason and at any point in the adoption process. 

To view our other wonderful Homeless Pets visit www.palsforpawsinc.com/pet-list ALSO be sure to LIKE Pals for Paws on Facebook at www.facebook.com/palsforpaws.inc 

All Pals for Paws Rescue animals are fully vetted:
*Spayed/Neutered
*Groomed
*Shots updated plus Leptospirosis 
*Micro-chipped
*Dewormed 
*On Heart-worm prevention
*On Flea and Tick Prevention
* Dentals are done if needed 

You only need to see your vet for a “meet n greet” of your new family member and to turn in their medical records.

Pals for Paws is a 501(c)3 animal rescue. Every penny donated and every penny received through adoption fees goes right back into the organization. There are times when the volunteers have to dip into their pockets to help the animals. We do not euthanize because a pet is sick, heart-worm positive, or has a broken leg; we fix it all, big and small. We strive to go above and beyond when caring for and socializing our animals. We understand the importance of getting to know each and every animal available for adoption in an effort to place them in the most perfect home possible. 
If you are looking for a particular type of dog or have special needs, We can help! Contact us at www.palsforpawsinc.com

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Dixie! Here is what would work best for me in my new home:

-Personality: Intelligent, active and very alert!
-Can Live with Kids: 16 and older due to sensitivity of environment and touch.
-Can Live with Cats: Unknown history, may be prey driven. Confident cats only. 
-Can Live with Dogs: Yes, a dog of similar play style (mellow, not rough and rowdy) who is tolerant to rude behavior. 
-Can do Apartment Living: No. Ideally Dixie would have a fenced in yard with plenty of space to exercise and explore daily. 
-Potty Trained: Appears to be! 
-Bite History: None 
-Positive Reward Based Obedience Classes Required: Yes, 1 private lesson to help bond with owner. 
-Energy Level: HIGH
-Needs Medical Procedure Before Going Home: Nope 
-Additional Information: Dixie has not taken well to the shelter life. With her increased stress levels it makes it difficult to see her true personality. With regular exercise and lots of mental stimulation, her anxiety levels should even out a bit more. Her Ideal home would understand and have experience with dogs who have high levels of anxiety or experience with separation anxiety. Dixie would do really well if she was given a "job" or if she was trained for agility. Her future home has to be committed to her mental health and ensure Dixie thrives once out of the shelter. Without proper care Dixie will become increasingly sensitive and for this reason she can not live in a home with young children.
animal.name: Dixie

animal.description:
Marlowe is an adorable 9 week old German Shepherd mix pup who was dumped on the streets of Bakersfield, and the people that found him made the right decision to seek rescue, as they were not in a position to take on another dog.  They wanted him to find a loving home that could properly care for him through his puppyhood and into his adulthood and the rest of his life.  He is very sweet- your typical shepherd.  Vocal, playful and active.  He's very smart, and shadows his person's every move.  He's wonderful around dogs, cats, chickens, everything he's met here at the rescue, and with good, continued socialization he will make a remarkable dog for someone or some family willing to take on a large breed puppy.
Marlowe is up to date on shots, neutered and microchipped.  Adoption fee $400.

animal.description:
Hugo is a very sweet 1-2 year old French Bulldog who ended up here quite unexpectedly.  Hes great with dogs around his size, boys or girls, and LOVES LOVES LOVES people.  He would be great in a home with the bulldog experience who knows how to manage a "high maintenance" breed such as he.  He would be best in a home without cats, as he doesn't have a super prey drive, but he gets a little too interested in them when they cross paths.
He's also a bigger guy, around 30lbs now with a few pounds to gain (maybe 5-7 more would be ideal), but a very athletic and sweet guy.  He'd be a great companion for good solid walks or jogging, and we would like to see him in a cooler climate than the central valley, with his snub nose and all. 
Hugo uses a dog door and seems to be housebroken in that regard.  He is also now up to date on shots, neutered and microchipped.  Adoption fee $850.

Sassafras is a feist who is about 2 yrs old and weighs 26 pounds.  She was owner surrendered to animal control because she wouldn't hunt.  She will tree the squirrel but runs when the gun is fired.  on the other hand she is happy to be a pet.  She's friendly, ready to cuddle and loves attention.  She is a little skittish which leads me to believe her previous owner didn't always treat her gently but she wants to please.

They are spayed or neutered, up to date on shots, de-wormed, heartworm tested (and treated if necessary), and on flea and heartworm prevention. animal.description:
*** MEDICAL HOLD*** 
***SPECIAL NEEDS***  
***FOSTERED IN TALLAHASSEE***
***FENCED IN YARD REQUIRED***

Ty is 2 yo deaf and vision impaired dane that is the product of unethical double merle breeding. He is the definition of gentle giant, he’s an absolute snuggle bunny, a constant shadow. He always has to be touching you, or lying on you. And he’s about 145 lbs.. so good luck moving from your spot on the couch if he’s on your legs.

Ty came to us from another rescue that was closing its doors and moving away. The reason he was surrendered to that rescue was because his owners couldn’t afford his vetting care and he was dealing with a very seriously infected and deep lick granuloma that covers almost his entire back ankle and leg. Lick granulomas are very hard to heal, they have to heal from the inside out and breathe (shouldn’t be bandaged up) and the dog’s licking just makes them get exponentially worse. It looks like a burn injury. Ty’s granuloma was covering almost his entire back leg. So now he’s on a very strict regimen of twice daily antibiotics, regular cleanings, and he has to be coned or muzzled to prevent him from constantly licking it when he’s not being directly observed.

This injury will take many months to fully heal. Whoever adopts Ty will need to understand that this will be a long recovery and he’s already become OCD about licking his legs when he’s bored, so he cannot be left alone without muzzle and cone on.

Ty is living with two other Great Danes, both males, one is 2 1/2 years old and the other one is nine years old, and he’s great with both of them. He also frequently lives with a female pug who comes over to play. He has never ever been aggressive with anything or anyone. He is the definition of love.

He is going to need a person or family that understands Danes and that can deal with a special needs dane as he is deaf and vision impaired. Luckily he has never seemed to mind and he is not one that gets spooked or scared easily.

A FENCED IN YARD IS REQUIRED.

Ty adoption fee is $400. He is neutered, fully vetted, and gastropexied.

To read over our adoption requirements and apply to adopt Ty please go to www.nwflgdr.com/adopt.

ATTENTION: NWFLGDR DOES NOT TRANSPORT. If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description:
Kiara / Female / 2 Years / 43 lbs / Street Mix / North York

Meet Kiara! Kiara has had a tough time finding the perfect home - but we know its out there! Her fosters describe her as a sweet and cuddly dog who loves giving kisses. She loves to play fetch and could go for hours. When she is indoors she likes squeaky toys, puzzle toys and stuffed kongs. Kiara is an active girl who would do best with a family who shares her loves of structured adventure. She is loving, loyal, high energy, playful and very smart. Kiara is looking for a special family who is committed to helping her reach her full potential!

When her foster parents come home, she is the happiest dog you’ll ever see. It took her a day or two to warm up to them but since then has been loving and friendly. Kiara is unsure of new people and can be reactive if her space isn’t respected. When people are calm and avoid eye contact or trying to pet her, generally she responds with a more balanced energy. Regardless her humans will need to advocate for her space and give new people firm instructions when entering her space. Adopters should have realistic expectations when meeting her, as it will take time to earn her trust.

When left alone Kiara is crated and needs someone to sit with her for her to settle. After a few minutes she will lie down for a nap, as long as she’s received enough exercise. Kiara is currently getting 2, 30 minute walks per day plus lots of time to play in the back yard. With adequate opportunities to use the washroom, Kiara is fully potty trained.

Kiara’s leash walking is a work in progress, as she is quite fearful of things outdoors. She is especially reactive to people in coats, other dogs, and sometimes cars/bicycles. She will bark or lunge to express her discomfort and demand her space. Her fosters are focused on clicker training and keeping Kiara on a familiar and predictable route for walks. Potential adopters should have experience with reactive dogs and a solid understanding of the work ahead with Kiara. They should also be willing to hire a professional trainer as needed.

Kiara is smart and picks up commands fairly quickly. Inside the home she has good focus, and knows sit and come. She needs a structured home environment so access to furniture and all valued items should be earned through training. Kiara currently sleeps in her crate and ideally this structure would continue in her forever home. She can sometimes confuse items around the home with her toys and chew them. She will need supervision at all times and adopters comfortable with consistent redirection.

Kiara’s ideal home would be a detached home, outside of the city. She will need a fully fenced backyard as its where she is most comfortable playing and enjoying outdoors. With her current level of reactivity she would not thrive in a city environment and is only looking for homes in quiet country or the suburbs. Kiara is dog selective and can be bossy and dominant in play. She has also shown some resource guarding with other dogs, so she would prefer to be the only pet in the home at this time. Kiara needs a a predictable and low activity household where she can really start to shine. Kiara is looking for adult-only homes.

If you’re interested in adopting Kiara please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Kiara’s adoption fee is $800. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

animal.description:
***FENCE REQUIRED*** ***MEDICAL HOLD***

Calamity is mismarked harl with piercing blue eyes. She’s affectionate with humans, a good cuddles, wants constant attention, and a bundle of nerves and energy. You see, Calamity fits her name... She is a wild child, always on the go.. and she can be very dominant, loud and bossy at play with other dogs. She needs slow introductions. And if she feels intimidated or threatened she gets more outwardly protective/dominant. It’s a defense mechanism with her it seems. 

We were told that Calamity is 2.5, but she honestly acts way younger than that. A total puppy. Calamity seems younger than her age  and she can act high strung at times around other dogs, which can be a lot to handle for other dogs. She plays like a puppy as far as energy level goes but is waaaay too dominant/ aggressive with her initiation and rough housing. But she's not actually trying to bite or hurt the other dog. She really just wants to play but doesn't know how to properly. She would do best in a home with very submissive playmate who will allow her to be rough and tumble and help wear her out. She WILL NOT do well in a house with a senior or any dog who doesn’t tolerate hyperactive well.. calamity is not the one for you. 

Calamity came from a backyard breeding bust. She came in with three other Danes when we pulled them from north Florida shelter in January. None had ever lived inside a home, so she’s learning potty training for the first time at 2. She isn't great about telling her foster parents she needs to go out but as long as they make sure she goes out regularly then she goes outside. Only two accidents so far.

She’s actually been very trustworthy and not gotten into anything when her foster parents are gone for work, for hours on end. 

Calamity will not be a good fit for a family with cats, young kids, farm animals or other dominant dogs. She’s just too much. She will absolutely require a fenced in yard.

Calamity is now fully vetted, vaccinated, spayed and chipped. Her adoption fee is $400. 

To read over our adoption requirements and apply to adopt Lacy please go to www.nwflgdr.com/adopt.

ATTENTION: NWFLGDR DOES NOT TRANSPORT. If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description:
Stormy is being fostered in Pennsylvania.

What we know about Stormy:
*mostly blind
*partially deaf
*housebroken, but has occasional accidents
*loves treats
*good with dogs and children

What Stormy's foster mom has to say about Stormy:
Stormy is such a sweet girl! That is the first thing the vet said after her first visit. She is not interested in toys but she loves to follow her people around the house and sleeps on her bed wherever they are. She loves ear rubs and neck scratches. She likes to go on neighborhood walks and prances around like a princess. She loves snacks, especially turkey and bacon. She is not a big couch cuddler but does love hugs and enjoys being held like a baby. She has lots of puppy dreams and even snores when she is in a deep sleep sometimes. It's so adorable! She has about 10-20% of her vision but she navigates around her environment quite well. We think she is partially deaf as well. She is housebroken, but does have occasional accidents. She is currently being treated for an eye infection and will follow up with the vet in one week to make sure it is cleared up. She's very tolerant of the eye drops and medications and getting brushed too. She is not much of a barker. She did well with the other dogs at the dog park but was not very interested in them. She is great around kids. Unknown how she is with cats but anticipate she would do well with them also. She is super laid back and just loves to be around people. We have fallen in love with her in a short amount of time. We know you will too!
BDRA has voted against the use of electrical fencing effective immediately.

animal.description:
***FOSTERED IN GULF BREEZE***

Blue is a giant sized lover boy who enjoy’s spending his time sun bathing out in the yard, napping the day away, or chewing a cow ear. He’s 5 years old and has a blissful calm temperament. But can be playful too, with the right playmate.  He’s never met a human he didn’t love! 

He’s currently in a foster home with a 2 year old female Great Dane & they get along great. Blu has also befriended 2 other female dogs that are family friends of his foster parents. A pitbull and a lab/heeler mix.  

The shelter Blue was rescued from mentioned he may not be good with male dogs and while we haven’t seen this completely in action; so far it does seem true since he throws a fit at the fence when his foster’s neighbor’s male Labrador is out in the yard at the same time as he is. 

Blue does know how to open doors for himself and isn’t shy about letting himself out for a tour of the front yard and to take a nice pee on the mailbox; so it’s important to ensure all doors and gates are secured. He knows how to sit and is working on other basic obedience commands too. 

Blue takes corrections quickly & proactively and is now crate trained and completely potty trained by doggy door; however when he is introduced to a new environment he may “mark” the new space with a few pee spots. This only happened a few times when initially arriving to his foster home. He’s also great on leash & loves walks. 

Blue has not been around any children while with his foster family but they believe he would be great with them, as long as they are big enough to not get smooshed!

Blue's adoption fee is $350. To read over our adoption requirements and apply to adopt Blue please go to www.nwflgdr.com/adopt.

ATTENTION: NWFLGDR DOES NOT TRANSPORT. If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

Meet Chance, our sweet and affectionate Rottweiler and German Shepherd mix. Chance is a friendly, adventurous and energetic young dog. He loves human attention but isn’t so sure around other dogs, he is very submissive around other dogs.

Chance is currently out of state, we are coordinating his rescue to Colorado, he is scheduled to arrive before the end of the month. He got picked up by animal control in Clovis, New Mexico. When he was picked up, he was already neutered so he obviously had a home before but no owner came for him at the shelter. We would like to put Chance straight into a trial adoption situation when he arrives. The process for that is the same and requires an adoption application.

Chance arrives fully vaccinated, neutered and microchipped, ready for his new Colorado home and lifestyle. He is around 1 year old and weighs 50lbs.

Chance knows just how miraculous a turn his life has taken when he was picked out by Havok’s Wolfpack and he is determined to live his new life to the fullest in the most adventurous way, hopefully, with you.

His adoption fee is $400

If you are interested in Chance, please submit an adoption application here:

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Our website has information about our rescue, adoption process and link to our adoption application
www.collarofhope.org

We are a foster home based rescue and have no facility to visit.
Prior to adoption, our dogs are spay/neutered, vaccinated including rabies/age appropriate, and parasite treated/prevented as a minimum.

ADELINA is a darling small chihuahua or mix of one. She is sometimes shy when meeting new people but once she's comfy, she loves her people. She is nervous when meeting new dogs until she's comfy with them too. But she just tolerates other dogs in her space and is not going to be your dogs new friend and playmate, she wants human attention not dog attention. We needed to be sure as she was a very protective Mama dog with her babies (all adopted now). It is her turn to be someone's baby instead of a baby maker. She doesn't care for the outside world much so her new family needs to be able to work with her on that or be prepared to have a potty pad girl. There were a lot of dogs in the home she came from so none learned much of anything and she's recently off Mama duty with us so we're just now able to work with her and really get to know Addy as a girl and not a mama dog.
She does NOT walk on leash so you MUST have a securely fenced yard that she cannot escape from and be willing to be outside with her so raptors don't snatch her up.
If you think Miss Addy might be the new companion for you, please submit our adoption application to get the process started.

Please visit our website directly to complete an online application.

animal.description:
***FOSTERED IN TALLAHASSEE*** 

***REQUIRES FENCED IN YARD***

Bocephus is a 18-24 mos old male dane who we pulled from a shelter in north Florida after he and several other Danes were surrendered by their breeder to the shelter.

Bo was very scared and guarded upon arrival to his foster home. He required very slow introductions to both his new humans and fellow pack companions.  Once he settled in, he quickly became your typical Velcro Dane and glued himself to his foster mom’s side. He seems more guarded with human males but within a few days, opens to them as well. He’s just learned that a couch is the best place to sleep and is more than happy to climb up into your lap and take a nap. 
 
Bo is basically a toddler who will need a watchful eye as he is still learning to be an indoor dog. He is a chewer and will need lots of toys to keep him occupied at all times. He is also a fan of socks and bras which his foster mom does not find as funny. He will also need a crate in his new home, or he will be destructive when left alone. He is fantastic at crating and does not fight going in or whine/bark when crated.  
 
Since he is learning to be an indoor dog, this also means he is working on going potty outside. He is picking up from his fellow pack quickly and starting to go to the door when he needs to go out. He has accidents here and there but will be a pro in no time.  
 
Bo is currently living with two other NWFLGDR alumni and a lab mix who he loves to play with. He doesn’t know his size and likes to body slam the lab mix who is about 50lbs so they have to have monitored playtime. He is an extremely rough player with all the dogs and would probably do better without a small dog to stomp on in his new home. There are two cats in the home as well however they stay separated from the dogs so we aren’t sure how he would react to them.
 
Now that Bo has made himself at home, we know that he is very loving, clumsy and playful. He is a sweet boy who just needs love, toys, a blanket to drag around and a good cartoon to watch every once in awhile. Bo is your typical Dane who deserves the best furever home possible.

Bocephus is neutered, vaccinated and chipped. His adoption fee is $400. 

To read over our adoption requirements and apply to adopt Bo please go to www.nwflgdr.com/adopt.

ATTENTION: NWFLGDR DOES NOT TRANSPORT. If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description:
Foster location:  Boise ID 
Breed:  Lab
Age:  12 years 
Size:  60 lbs
Adoption Fee:  $50.00
Spayed, Vaccinated, Microchipped

Adoption Application:  http://fuzzypawzrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application-2/

Mischa came to Fuzzy Pawz after finding herself in a local shelter.  This poor thing had a bunch of nasty growths all over her body including a deep one on her head that bled constantly!  She also had giardia and a wicked ear infection.  We had the lumps removed and got the other issues cleared up; it took months but she is now ready to find a forever home.
She is the sweetest girl who is all about enjoying the retirement phase of her life. Her foster family has affectionately named her “The Lounge Princess”, as that is her favorite daily activity. Her other favorite activity is eating, which she does with gusto. Even though she can’t read a clock, she always knows when it’s mealtime, and will make sure you do too! Her foster family has only ever heard her bark a handful of times in the several months they have had her, and every time it was just a single “woof” when they weren’t getting her meal quickly enough!
While Mischa likes to take it easy and relax most of the day, she does still enjoy getting outside for short, slow walks around the block where she can get some good sniffs. Being a senior dog, Mischa has a few ongoing treatments her new owners will need to commit to. She has some arthritis, which is why she doesn’t move very fast, is deaf in both ears (due to untreated ear infections), and since she came to Fuzzy Pawz she has been diagnosed with Cushing’s Disease. This condition makes her have increased appetite and thirst, heat intolerance, and a weakened immune system. She is on daily medication which she will need to continue for the rest of her life.  As a side-effect of Cushing’s Disease, she also has multiple benign sebaceous cysts on her skin. She has had several of the larger ones removed while with Fuzzy Pawz, but these will also be something she will deal with the rest of her life.
Despite some health conditions, she is very easy to take care of and will be your most loyal companion. She is house-trained, crate-trained, has learned hand signals for “come”, “sit”, and “stay”, and does great on a leash. She gets along well with other dogs. It is unknown how she is with children and cats. Although she has shown no aggression with either when she has encountered them on walks; that being said we would prefer a quiet/calm household with no kids under 15.
We will be honest it is not likely that Mischa will live more than 6-12 months; but she is 100% worth living her best life with people who love her!

If you’re looking for a loving, easy-going couch potato to add to your family, Mischa is you.

Duchess certainly lives up to her name, as this gorgeous hound mix has a commanding personality that simply cannot be ignored! Despite being 4 years old, she still has quite a bit of playful energy and is a silly, spunky girl! She:
•	Is house trained
•	Weighs 80 pounds
•	Is good with other respectful dogs
•	Enjoys going for car rides
•	Has lived with cats

Playing, exploring, walking, swimming - Duchess loves to live life to the fullest and is always happily tapping her feet! Despite losing her owner in December she has remained vivacious and affectionate. Every person she meets is a friend, and she will bring so much fun and laughter to her new home. 

Duchess came to us with her mom Rockie. Although they do not need to be adopted into the same home, it would be wonderful to see them go together! Would you consider taking them both? 

Duchess is spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and heartworm negative.

animal.description:
***FOSTERED IN TALLAHASSEE***

Lacy, 2.5 yo merle, good with all, so calm and gentle.

It’s clear that Lacy was a backyard breeder dane and used for birthing puppies. This former mama is easily adjusting to being an inside dane.  She is so very sweet and delicate as the word “lacy” may describe. She loves snuggles and wants to be as close as possible to her human.  
Lacy came to us with a skin and eye infection we are treating and seems to be recovering well.

Lacy currently lives with single Foster mom with 3 cats, a lab/pit mix and old lady lab.  This girl is so sweet and gentle. She loves to snuggle.

Foster mom thinks she may have some basic obedience for sit and down, but “off” just means switch to the other couch.  

She is good in the crate and will go to the crate when there is lots of work/activity in the house, but don’t be fooled she wants to be with her human. Lacy hasn’t display chewing behaviors and we haven’t found her high value toy just yet.  She prefers to snuggle on the bed and with her human.

Lacy hasn’t been exposed to children with foster Mom, but this girl is very calm so we feel she will be just fine.
Cats: She plays with foster mom’s indoor/outdoor cat who seems to understand chase play. So chase cats are good and she is very indifferent to the other two cats.

Lacey is gentle and kind and the definition of good. She is now spayed and vaccinated and chipped. She is being treated for a skin infection and I’ll and ear infection and will need to continue her antibiotic regimen.

Lacy’s adoption fee is $400. To read over our adoption requirements and apply to adopt Lacy please go to www.nwflgdr.com/adopt.

ATTENTION: NWFLGDR DOES NOT TRANSPORT. If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description:
Greta, a year old, is a big, beautiful, and loving girl.  She has a serious demeanor and is mellow by nature.  She likes long naps and exploring large outdoor spaces.  She likes to play with her canine companion and take long walks with her humans.  She is cautious meeting new people and dogs, but warms up well.  She is good on the leash, house trained (uses a pet door), and crate trained (sleeps here at night).  Greta likes car rides, but prefers to be front and center with a view out the windshield.  This fits her personality as she is a confident girl who likes to be in charge.  Greta knows basic commands like sit and stay, but is working on reactive resource guarding behavior.  She will need ongoing work in this area with an experienced owner who can provide the love, structure, and training she needs.

Greta was born to working pyrenees on a ranch in Wyoming and came to Lucky's Place with her litter mates as a young pup. She has spent her first year living with a family who love her very much, but sadly are unable to keep her.  Greta needs a home with a big yard to explore and play and would do well with a canine  companion close to her own age and size.  Although Greta is used to being around children and is quite fond of them, she would do best in a home without children as she needs the consistent guidance of a confident leader who is familiar with pyrenees behavior traits and committed to her ongoing training and socialization.  Greta has been gently curious about other small pets, but has not lived with cats.  She is not the lap dog type, but more of a sit at attention by your side kind of girl.  Greta is a perfect hiking partner and will be a faithful steady companion for the right owner.

She was also examined for a dental and, a dental was not recommended at this time. 

Incomplete applications will not be reviewed. If you have used veterinary services in the past please list them on the application. We do check references and perform a home visit.

animal.description:
Who else is riding on the Freeway of Love and looking to find their doggo soul mate in the process? Fall in love? Live happily ever after? Well, we have your Aretha right here at SG and you and she will likely be singing and humming from here on out, together forever. Aretha is just about the sweetest, prettiest hound around, although she is somewhat shy and does not seem to know just how spectacular she really is. Aretha is about 2 or so years old and is underweight at about 50 lbs. Girlfriend has long legs and gorgeous long hound ears, a beautiful tri colored coat and loves the outdoors, roaming and sniffing with her hound nose. Aretha has day by day been getting a little more confident and will continue to bloom in a home, ideally with other dogs, as she finds companionship in dogs and will do well to have one who leads the way and helps her to build her confidence. Aretha would love a fenced in yard and would likely do well with slightly older children as she is still shy and not used to lots of loud noises and games of hide and go seek. Aretha would love to earn your respect and win your heart in 2021!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

Age:  10 years old
Adoption Fee:  $100.00
Spayed, Vaccinated, recently had a dental

If interested you MUST complete the Adoption Application:  http://fuzzypawzrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application-2/

Little Roxy was not doing well in her home due to a new child in her home so Fuzzy Pawz agreed to take her in and find her a kid free, quit, loving place to retire!

Roxy LOVES her people and wants to be with them always she enjoys love walks, snuggling on the couch and sleeping with her humans (under the covers if they will let her). This little girl will follow you everywhere if you let her. She is an amazing companion.  She does get a little anxious when left home alone; she does better if she has a doggie companion but still misses her humans if they leave her.  The perfect home for her would be someone who is home more often than not; it needs to be pretty quiet without a lot of goings-on and she needs a consistent schedule.

Roxy knows basic commands (sit, down, stay and we are working on "dogs in the kitchen" which means all the dogs are to leave the kitchen area).  She is very spunky and loves riding in the car.  She does bark to alert you if someone is at the door.  Roxy can be a runner if given the chance – in her previous home she escaped the house on occasion and twice was hit by a car (she doesn’t seem to have any residual issues from these).

Good with dogs her size that aren’t too pushy and she is living with a cat with no issues.  NO kids under 15 please.

A dental was just completed and Roxy had to have 7 teeth pulled and she has a bit of arthritis but is otherwise healthy.

Roxy is fully house trained and can use a dog door.

animal.description:
Look at that award winning smile! Lucas flashes it all the time outside where he enjoys playing with toys, being chased through the yard, or just sniffing around. He's never smiling in his kennel though where he spends most of his day. Lucas is one of those sweet dogs who just can't stand being cooped up at the shelter, and is finding the whole experience extremely stressful and depressing. He would like to get out of the shelter as soon as possible by going into a foster or forever home!

Lucas doesn't seem reactive to other dogs, and already seems to have some basic training on board but can be very pushy and jumpy at certain times.

At 2 yrs old and 53 lbs, Lucas is a lovely size, especially since much of his weight is soft silky golden coat! Because Lucas can be a lot when he is stressed or excited, he is looking for a family without children under 12 yrs old. He has been neutered, vaccinated, heart worm tested (negative), microchipped, and is current on parasite prevention.

HOW TO FOSTER
Click on tulsaspca.org/become-foster-parent and complete the Foster Application. You can follow up with foster@tulsaspca.org. Use subject line FOSTER LUCAS. Thank you for your interest in becoming a foster parent.

HOW TO ADOPT
The Tulsa SPCA is currently operating on an appointment-only basis.
- Click on the orange "Interested in this animal? Click here!" button to apply to adopt.
- If you're approved, we'll contact you to finalize the paperwork, collect payment and arrange an appointment for your drive-thru adoption.
- Please stay home if you feel unwell, especially if you are experiencing symptoms of fever, cough or sore throat.
Thank you for your patience and understanding during this time. These policies may change as the Tulsa SPCA makes adjustments in response to the ongoing situation.

animal.description:
I LOVE LONG WALKS IN THE WOODS!

THE BASICS:

Lab/Rottweiler mix; black and brindle
ADULT MALE; EST DOB: November 2018
ARRIVAL: October 10, 2020
HISTORY:  Teddy was transferred from DCHS in South Carolina.  Teddy was an owner surrender to a high kill shelter.  The reason for surrender, “He’s too shy.”   Teddy really struggled at the county shelter and was an easy target to be put down so we spoke up for him before it was too late.  We’re really glad we did!!
 

When Teddy first arrived, he was scared and would bark at anyone who got too close, though he would never lunge or bite.  Teddy simply wanted to make it clear that he would like to be left alone.  Beneath his blustery exterior, though, is a really sweet dog.  When you look away from him he’ll inch closer to sniff you.  He wants love, but he isn’t sure how to open himself up to it just yet.  Some of our more dog-savvy volunteers are able to walk him and they can’t praise him enough!  Once he gets over his apprehension enough to let someone put a leash on him, Teddy is a completely different dog.  He’s friendlier and grows in confidence.  It will take time and patience to fully earn Teddy’s trust, but we encourage you to come sit with this gentle, loving soul and help him feel more at ease.

Comments from Volunteer at County Kill Shelter:  I have a tail that wags!  Won’t you come and check it out please?  Folks have been saying I am “shy,” in fact that was the reason my person turned me into the local shelter.  I would beg to differ (a bit!) ….just ask the nice volunteers who got me out for a nice easy going walk along with 2 other well balanced dogs.   My tail wagged AND I smiled!  I did look both ways out of caution when I exited the busy shelter kennel area but the further I got from all the noise and chaos, the more relaxed I became.  Like many self respecting dogs,  I really don’t want you to immediately drape yourself on me or get right in my face.  Please, won’t you give me a wee bit of time for me to first check out YOU?  My tail was tightly tucked initially on our journey but as you can see from the photos,  I proudly put it on display once I was comfortable.  I am a pretty polite, mild mannered fellow who is sweet and gentle natured. A fenced in yard where I can run and explore and sniff and relax would be an incredible way for me to get some fresh air and exercise.  You should see me as I trot around with confidence in one of the fenced areas at the shelter!   Loud noise and lots of energy around me is not a great choice for me so a home with a more laid back couple (or person) perhaps with a well balanced dog (not sure i want some high energy, zooming dog to play with) to hang out with, would help me be at my best and love on YOU the best.    Ask for me, Teddy today won’t you?

animal.description: Macky came to the Shelter as a stray. He was very nervous when arriving - moving away from people and preferring to hide. After some office TLC at the Shelter with some confident dogs - Macky blossomed! Macky is currently in a foster home with one of our wonderful dog volunteers as well as two resident dogs - a large breed male dog and a smaller female dog. He is learning about all things dog and making great strides in his confidence. Macky gains a lot of confidence from following his foster dog brother and sister around. When the resident dogs to their moms for attention, Macky joins in in seeking out TLC! Slowly but surely, he has armed up to hanging out in his foster's laps and snuggling. Once Macky is comfortable, he LOVES pets and scratches. Macky is still working on housetraining and was recently neutered. Macky is a sweet guy who is looking for a patient person who is willing to take his transition into his new home slowly. A confident resident dog in the home is required. A home with cats may be appropriate with a slow introduction and management. Kids are not recommended in the home due to Macky's fear. JNG

animal.description:
This sweet, sweet girl is Tessa.

K9 Kindness rescued Tessa and her three adult puppies from an outdoor living situation after their family experienced a tragedy. Tessa has been spayed and updated on all of her shots, so she is ready to find a brand new home. She is somewhat submissive and gets along with other dogs; it may just take her a while to come out of her shell. No cats, please. She is house-trained and will tolerate a kennel, but it's not her favorite place, can't say we blame her!

If you think a three year old, 50 pound, beautiful, dark brindle dog is too big for a lap dog, you haven't met Tessa. She is confident that she fits in just about anywhere. On the couch next to you is OK, but her head on your lap would be preferable. She's about 16 inches high at her shoulder and is a mixed breed. She walks well on a leash and is only moderately interested in toys.

Tessa is not a wild girl that needs to be entertained a lot - just a nice quiet laid-back girl who only wants to please you. This girl has a sweet and gentle soul and wants to be your companion and share your life.

Tessa is UTD on shots, preventative, micro-chipped, and spayed!

Tessa's adoption fee is $250, and adopters must live within 175 miles of the Quad City Area.

If interested in meeting Tessa you must fill out the online application at www.k9kindnessrescue.org/adopt/application

Tessa and K9 Kindness Rescue thank you for considering adoption through rescue for your new family companion!

animal.description:
Are Stella and Piper still available?? 

(Unfortunately, we will not reply to emails asking this question as we do not have the time or volunteers to do so. We update our website daily just so you will know the status right away).  PLEASE GO TO OUR WEBSITE for up to date information to find out.  Check the Gallery by putting your mouse on the photo.  IF it says Pending, we chose someone, but they haven't met up yet.  If it says Adopted, then the dog has been happily united with a forever family.  IF nothing is there other than their name, they are still available.

APPLY if interested so you can be considered.?

*Our page is updated daily. Please go to www.wowdogrescue.org for any updates.

The family of Stella and Piper have run up against a hardship.  The owner is having some medical issues and they are unable to hold on to these  2 sweet gals any longer.  They called us asking if we thought anyone would be able to keep these 2 together, as they enjoy each others company so much.  Most dog owners appreciate having 2 dogs that can entertain or comfort each other while they are away.

Stella is a light brown chi-weenie who is 1 yr old.  She is spay, chipped and up to date on immunization shots.  She loves her food so needs to ne portioned out for her vs leaving a bowl out all day.  She weighs in around 12 lbs.  She also is great with potty outside with a doggy door..

Piper is the small black pup who is 8 mos old and they were told she is a Maltese / chihuahua mix.  She weighs in around  7 lbs.  She is also spay, Microchipped and up to date on immunization shots.  She knows the doggy door for potty too.

Both are a little shy at first but are fine with kids  but both are skittish at 1st. They seem fine with other small dogs and they have full run of the downstairs at night time.  If you are looking for a pair of sweet little girls who are young enough to learn you and your routines, please apply.

As a Bonded pair these 2 young girls adoption fee is set at $275.00

WE ARE NOT PETFINDER.  WE ARE NOT ADOPTAPET, OR RESCUE ME.  Our application is on our website:  www.wowdogrescue.org 

**PLEASE do not call or email to see if they are "still" available.  The Gallery photo on our website will be updated daily and will state their status.  IF we have chosen someone, they will be marked "Pending".  IF they have been adopted, they will be marked "Adopted".

***Tired of not finding, or not being chosen for the dog of your dream?? 
 Consider Fostering with us...Our Fosters have 1st chance at adopting the dog they foster, while we pay for everything.  Its a win win for both! YOU get to see if this is a good match for your family, while the dog is being loved in your home...

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Mixed breed puppiesHolly is such a sweet, mixed breed dog. We are totally guessing on her breed mix, she looks like a herding breed mix,could be a Canaan mixed dog: https://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/canaan-dog/ or a Carolina dog mix https://www.akc.org/dog-breeds/carolina-dog/ (lesser known breeds) but she looks similar to this. She could have some Shepherd, Husky or Heeler in her too? So again we are guessing on her breed mix.

Holly is approximately 30 lbs and 2-3 years old. Holly came to us with 4 puppies. They were all in the pound together and a couple of the pups got parvo and they all spent a week at the vet getting treatments and were cleared of it on 12-30-20, having all survived.

Holly is a sweet, sensitive under socialized soul. She is doing well in foster, and making progress but she will need an understanding home that will be patient with her. You have to kind of approach her like a cat, on her terms. She wants to be with you but on her own terms, until she can trust. She doesn't have an aggressive bone in her body but will flinch and avoid in fear. She loves the foster home's 15 year old daughter and even sleeps in her bed now with her, so you can see she craves companionship she just is choosy on who she trusts at this point.

We think she needs a home with a fenced in yard and another dog for security purposes and for her best life (Another dog to teach her confidence, and to soothe her psychologically).

Interested in adopting? Please complete a pre-adoption application at https://redemptionroadrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=4003.

McGinnis is a 4 year old Anatolian Shepherd/Great Pyrenees mix. He is a BIG boy & still trying to gain some weight with quality food & healthy toppings his foster mom spoils him with. 
McGinnis is being fostered with 2 male cavalier King Charles spaniels and a dog-savvy 6 year old. Due to his size and playfulness, McGinnis is may not a good option for small children. Though he is kind to his foster brother dogs, he can be picky with others. So he will have to do a meet & greet to determine if it's a good fit. 
McGinnis was found as a very underweight stray with a collar embedded in his neck. The collar was surgically removed and he was also neutered. He is heart worm negative & all healed now! McGinnis is VERY smart & would be best for someone familiar with Anatolians/Pyrenees. He can open latch doors on his own and is kitchen counter and table top height, though he is amazingly good at not attacking available food considering he easily could. McGinnis walks best on a leash with a gentle lead to reduce his pulling as he is so strong & would love to chase all wild rabbits and squirrels. McG does jump up when excited to meet new people at his foster home and would benefit from training. He gives his foster mom occasional kisses & loooooves belly rubs. He sleeps on a giant dog bed at the end of his foster mom's bed, but loves to dog-bed hop and try to fit in beds of any size. He has learned to enjoy car rides & despite initially being scared, ended up loving his first bath & towel rub down. He requires at least one walk a day or he is BORED. McGinnis keeps an eye on the guinea pigs in his foster home as well as human children when they are over to play. McGinnis is an incredibly smart, loyal, & loving dog who seeks a person or family that will appreciate him and take wonderful care of him for life! 

To set up a meet and greet or inquire about a dog, please first fill out an application at https://savinghoperescue.org/contact. It doesn't obligate you, but it is the first step. We don't get to all of the inquiries but respond to all applications. Thank you for choosing to rescue!

animal.description:
Sharky is a handsome 7-year-old male Havanese that weighs 16 pounds. He is the sweetest little guy that will make the perfect companion for anyone! He is blind from advanced cataracts, but can navigate a home and yard once he figures out his surroundings. He loves exploring the backyard, enjoys the company of other dogs, is fantastic with small kids, and is very social. He is an easy going and low maintenance dog. He is neutered, vaccinated, heartworm negative, and microchipped. He is $350 plus TX sales tax with an approved application: www.recycledpomsbcs.com/adopt

Texas law requires that all humane organizations (Rescues, SPCA's, Humane Societies, State nonprofit, and charitable 501c3 exempt orgs) collect and remit sales and use tax to the Texas Comptroller on their adoption fees.

We do not ship or transport our dogs. We require all adopters to meet the dog in person to ensure it is a good fit. We represent the dog to the best of our ability and since they are in rescue, we do not always get their history.

Please note: We are a non-profit Pomeranian Rescue with dogs in private foster homes. We do not have a facility open to the public. We require an approved application before a potential adopter is introduced to a dog. We contact vet references to ensure animals in the home are current on vaccinations, heart worm prevention, and sterilization. We do not adopt our dogs to homes in which an animal is not spayed or neutered. A home visit may be required.

Please visit our website for more information and an adoption application. www.recycledpomsbcs.com

animal.description:
Chihuahua Mix – Female – 9 lbs – 5 yrs (approx.)

Paddy is a 9 lb., 5-year-old female Chihuahua mix coming to us from a Tennessee shelter. She is chocolate brown with a tan and brown brindle face. She is micro chipped, has had her teeth cleaned and received her rabies in March of 2020. There are no known health issues.

This wee girl has had a very tough 5 years making her an exceptionally fearful dog. Paddy lived in a hoarding situation her entire life until rescued earlier in 2020. She was placed in a foster home in Tennessee until she could come to us, which she did July 31.

She is extremely fearful of new people and will curl into a ball facing the wall. She has a hard time meeting other dogs, keeping them away with aggressive growls. I believe this is caused from her poor start where she had to fight for food with the other dogs in her situation. to escape being close to them. In new situations, she is prone to defense biting when cornered and pursued, which intensifies her already extremely high level of fear.

When she first came to me in July, she was in a restricted living area, usually curled up into a tight ball facing the back of the carrier, not making eye contact and snarling if one of the house dogs got too close to the pen. She especially did not like the cats getting close, she will lunge and snarl at them. She did come out and eat and take treats left for her only if no people or dogs were in the room.

Today she has full reign of the house. She has bonded with the dogs, running and wrestling with them, playing fetch and sleeping with them on the couch, where she doesn’t mind the cats sleeping beside her. She is definitely food motivated, loving her meals and treat times. She lines up with the pack at the kitchen door when I am in the kitchen, hoping something drops which she can scoop.

When I come in, she is with the pack at the door greeting me with a wriggling body and wagging tail! In the house she has become my shadow. She will take treats from my hand, gives me lots of little kisses – on my feet or ankles. She has just started to let me tickle her chin, only a couple of flicks and she backs away. This is the first contact she has allowed.

Paddy has made great strides and will continue to do so if allowed the time and security to do so in her own time. She is in no way over her fear and lack of trust of people and new animals, but she has started on this journey of acceptance. One can see it in her face and behavior.

She needs a home where her people have the patience and understanding to allow her to continue developing her trust of people and animals. She should go to a mature and quiet home. Definitely no children. A fenced yard is a must as she is a flight risk. It would benefit Paddy to have a calm canine sibling, so she can learn the appropriate behaviors.

Her forever people need to understand that she is definitely a work in progress and that she might never be a cuddly girl but with their help she will be a loving girl.

For more information on Paddy, please contact Jackie at jackie.brossard1952@gmail.com

OR visit our website: www.savemedogrescue.ca

** Adoptions within the province of Ontario only

animal.description: I like big girls, I can't deny. And when they are as drop dead gorgeous as this one, well, I'm hooked. At forty-seven-pounds she has pretty much reached her full size unless you go treat crazy which is pretty easy with such a loving dog. The thing about Lady is that she plays nicely with other dogs in a group or on walks but she loves being the only dog in the home. For that reason we believe she will be best in a home where she can get and give all the doggy love and not worry about competition. Four is a great age to add a dog into your home but even though she has already developed some nice manners she will have to learn the ins and outs of your home and she will get acclimated soon. If you have a thing for black dogs with happy smiles then you'll want to see Lady soon. She lives up to her name in every way! Lady is up to date on her vaccinations, is spayed, and will be microchipped before going to her forever home. animal.description:
Lilly is a 7 year old 4 lbs Chihuahua mix who is currently looking for her fur-ever home. She is up to date on vaccines, dewormed, and spayed. 

Rescued from: Los Angeles area. 
Likes: She likes her soft food in a saucer ( easier to eat from) & loves to roll on her back (see video) She has no teeth & loves treats she can eat.
Dislikes: When new people come to visit or knock on the door. She suddenly finds her very loud barking voice. Tell her “No “ and she does quiet down after a while.
Ideal Home: Lily’s ideal home will have another small easy-going dog & no children and no large breed dogs. Have access to a backyard as she does not like walks. Have patience with housetraining and be very gentle with this extra small girl.
Energy Level: Low. 
Experience with Kids: Unknown but not recommended. 
Experience with cats: Unknown.
Medical Needs: Lily had some mammary tumors removed and they were benign. There is a slight chance they may come back in other places.
Training Needs: Lily is working in house training. She uses pee pads & seems familiar with them. A backyard where u can let her out often would be helpful for her small bladder.

From Lilly's Foster: 
Lily is a confident & sassy, sweet little girl. She has bursts of energy and then wants to cuddle in a blanket. She will follow you everywhere to see what you are doing. She sits nicely in the morning after getting up, as she knows breakfast is coming. She could use a little more weight, so gets fed soft food 3 times a day. She is a smart little girl but does not like walks, but think that will change once summer is here. She has started to reverse sneeze whee when she eats too fast or gets excited. She will be a great companion & enjoys another small dog. Due to her small size, her home will need to have no larger breed dogs & children in it.



As all of our dogs are currently in private foster homes if you would like more in-depth information about this dog, Please follow us on facebook at www.facebok.com/fureverhomesdogs and attend our adoption events to meet our current adoptables and fill out an adoption application.

Fur-ever Homes Rescue is a registered Canadian Charity run entirely by volunteers and generous donations. 

http://www.fur-everhomesrescue.com/

animal.description:
Meet Benjamin Button. He’s a sweet, dog/cat friendly, 15 lb senior poodle [exact age not known but he could be 15] who is deaf and mostly blind. He was found as a stray and had clearly suffered from neglect for a long period of time. When his foster first picked him up, it seemed he had no spirit left in him. Luckily, with some TLC and a much needed dental surgery, Benjamin is starting to come back to life. 

Despite being blind/deaf, this little guy is pretty adaptable once he figures out his space and routine. If he does get lost or needs something, he will communicate with you through a bark. 

I think his bio might be misleading. People will see 10 year old poodle and think he’s still pretty young.  

BB enjoys using his nose to find hidden treats around the house, sniffing around the backyard and napping in comfy beds. If you give him a good neck scratch and some yummy treats, he will love you forever! 

Benjamin deserves a loving home, but an adopter should know that he's in the later stages of being a senior and will not be a dog that wants to go on walks or do much besides sleep, eat and wander. 

We are still evaluating Benjamin Button’s cognitive health, so be sure to check back for updates! An adopter for Benjamin would need to be prepared for an adjustment period until he figures out his space and routine.

animal.description:
Wendy is a 6 year old 20 lbs Chihuahua mix who is currently looking for her fur-ever home. She is up to date on vaccines, dewormed, and spayed. 

Rescued from: Los Angeles area. 
Likes: Chasing and catching balls, stuffed toys, and snuggling.
Dislikes: Being picked up, being on her back & doesn't like riding in the car but the more exposure she gets, the better she is.
Ideal Home: Wendy's ideal home would be a home with another dog. Detached home due to barking at things when she looks out the window and a securely fenced yard.
Energy Level: Medium. 
Experience with Kids: Unknown.
Experience with cats: Unknown.
Medical Needs: None at this time.
Training Needs: Wendy needs some basic training, she walks well on a loose leash and really enjoys being with her people. Wendy is currently working with our dog training to help her overcome her anxiety related to meeting new people and new dogs. She can be a bit shy/ fearful in those situations. She is pee pad trained.

From Wendy's Foster: 
Wendy is a very loving dog. She's very playful first thing in the morning and will bring you a toy to throw while you are getting ready. She loves to play fetch with a ball and loves stuffed toys that she can shake. She enjoys playing tug of war but she won't give up. Wendy is fearful of new people and will run and hide. It takes Wendy sometimes to trust people and learn that they aren't going to hurt her. With lots of love and patience, Wendy will bond with you and then becomes your best friend. She has similar behavior to new dogs she meets and it takes her some time to warm up, however, once she is comfortable she does enjoy playing. Wendy doesn't really like to be picked up but she does enjoy sitting on your lap. Wendy is a sweet and loving girl who may appear shy at first but given time, will turn into your best friend...Are you Wendy's new best friend??

As all of our dogs are currently in private foster homes if you would like more in-depth information about this dog, Please follow us on facebook at www.facebok.com/fureverhomesdogs and attend our adoption events to meet our current adoptables and fill out an adoption application.

Fur-ever Homes Rescue is a registered Canadian Charity run entirely by volunteers and generous donations. 

http://www.fur-everhomesrescue.com/

animal.description:
Vanni is a 5 year old 35 lbs Beagle mix who is currently looking for her fur-ever home. She is up to date on vaccines, dewormed, and spayed. 

Rescued from: Local surrender.
Likes: Playing tug-o-war, going for walks, playing fetch & snuggling (a LOT!). Running around the yard & playing with her people.

Dislikes: Being left alone, Being ignored & Car rides.
Ideal Home: Vanni's ideal home will have someone home for the majority of the day. She needs lots of love, patience, and reassurance. She needs someone with some dog training experience (or a willingness to learn) as she is still working through some bad habits.
Energy Level: Medium.
Experience with Kids: Yes, ok. 
Experience with cats: Yes, ok.
Medical Needs: Vanni has epilepsy and is on medication to control it. Vanni also has food allergies and is on a hypoallergenic diet.

Training Needs: Vanni is working on manners while she is on a leash and she is also learning to stay away from kitchen counters and the kitchen table She is very smart and motivated by food so that will be helpful with training. 

From Vanni's Foster: 
Vanni has been with us for almost 3 months and after a week of getting to know one another, we absolutely fell in love with her. She is patient with children, loves to be snuggled, and gets along very well with other dogs and cats. Vanni loves being around people and she believes wholeheartedly that she is a lap dog. Once she warms up to you Vanni will follow you everywhere and sleep at your feet (or, preferably, on you) if you're sitting and relaxing. She needs a family that has patience and is able to work with her every day. Vanni does not like to be left alone and has separation anxiety when she doesn't feel safe and her people are not nearby. She is probably the sweetest dog we have ever fostered and will make her forever family feel lucky to have her.
love to give and a family with a lot of patience. She will be your best friend for life once she trusts you.

This sweet girl is a little timid here but we think she is just subdued due to the commotion that happens on a dailiy basis here.  Once she gets comfortable we know she will be less timid.  If you don't know anything about Catahoulas here's some brief information but we encourage you to do your research.  Catahoula Leopard Dogs are natural born hunters and herders. Ursula lived with other dogs in the Alabama rescue she was at but she was adopted and didn't get along with another dog in the home.  She got along with male dogs really well at the rescue. Whenever people come up to me, I can't help but wiggle my butt hoping to get some scratches and my favorite head rubs. I haven’t been tested with kids, but my foster parents think I will be a great growing up buddy, because I am very friendly and I take treats so gently. I would prefer a family with another dog to keep me company or a family who would keep me by their side since I am still little and not used to be alone by myself. I am food motivated; I learned to sit for treats quickly, and with some proper training I will be your perfect pup. I am also crate trained, no accident at all in my crate so far. I love to play with all toys and the occasional shoe but I'm a quick learner and can be redirected back to my toys easily. I am pretty good at keeping myself occupied with my toys when my foster parents are working at their desk, so if you work from home I'll mind my manners and be ready to love on you when you take a break! Pick me to be your forever pup! Rizzo is a Black Lab mix, weighs 26 lbs (but growing!) and was born approximately 9/23/2020. She is spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, given flea/tick preventive, dewormed & started on heartworm preventive. Adoption fee is $550 to help offset the many expenses we have for vetting costs. animal.description:
Please contact Linda for more information about this pet.Meet the beautiful Anna! '
To start Anna is only being rehomed because they have a kitty. No other reason given. This is the owners story of ANNA!

Anna is a pretty girl that gets lots of compliments. She is very much a typical shepherd in that she loves to be with her people. She has been a mostly indoor dog, with time spent in the backyard to play and go to the bathroom. She's playful and affectionate and although she still has some puppy energy, she settles easily and naps often. She was raised with another dog and two young children. Her size might annoy my 3 year old son sometimes, but I often find him laughing while they play together in the yard. Her basic manners and commands are strong. She doesn't jump, knows not to get on the couch or bed, and will sit and wait for her food even though she's very excited. She has never exhibited any food or toy aggression.

She's intelligent and curious, but definitely needs these tendencies to have a productive outlet. She's very food motivated so training with treats is quite effective. She has had a lot of experience walking around the neighborhood with our dog, kids, strollers, and my son on his scooter. I use a front clip harness and she rarely pulls. She enjoys and benefits from regular walks. It doesn't take much to wear her out thankfully.

She has socialized with other dogs and people on a limited basis due to Covid. But she has spent time with other family dogs while on a family trip to Tahoe. And it went well! When people do visit, she's always friendly and receptive to visitors.

She is fully potty trained and now sleeps loose in our bedroom on her dog bed.

Come see this pup on Saturdays during adoption event hours. Please email Linda at lbredfire@sbcglobal.net or call WT&F's Dog Team voicemail 707-812-9030 to get a jump on the process, ask questions, and/or to confirm they will be there. Dog adoptions are held outside Napa Petco every Saturday - 12:30pm to 4:00pm.
This dog comes spayed/neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, dewormed, heartworm tested negative, and more with an adoption fee/donation to Whiskers, Tails and Ferals in Napa, CA. See more information at http://whiskerstailsandferals.org/.
Visit our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/whiskerstailsandferals/

animal.description:
Meet amazing Eloise! She is an active senior at 9 1/2 years young. 
Adorable and a lovely mix of Chihuahua and terrier to make for a cute and compact 40lb. medium-sized doll. Eloise has such a bright spirit and is ready to go anytime. She will get you out for walks, make you laugh, give you love, and cuddle with you! She prefers a calmer household so no kiddo's or other pets please.  She is Ok with apt living as long as she gets ample time outdoors with walks. If you have a yard, even better!  She will do best with an experienced owner rather than a first-time pup parent. 

Eloise really wants you to herself and is not into other dogs. She can get overly excited if they get to close but responds to redirection. She walks well on the leash, is house trained, knows a few tricks and has a bright personality that keeps you smiling and on your toes. This cutie pie loves human companionship, will be your best friend, and will take ear scratches and belly rubs as often as you will give them.  She will take a little time to settle into your home, and we will give you tips on how to ease her in. She is in great health and shows no signs of slowing down. She is current on all shots, spayed, and micro-chipped.
Upon adoption we will provide a transition session!

Potus is a very sweet boy but is still very Aloof toward people. He is completely fine being around people but gets very nervous when someone tries to touch him. 

Potus needs to be with other dogs, he will not do well as a only dog. He seems to find comfort in other dogs and being around other dogs seems to help him with his insecurities. 

Potus is making a lot of progress in the short time that he has spent in foster. He is learning how to walk on leash and getting better at it each day. Potus is going to need someone who is going to be able Be very patient with him and understand that it is going to take time for him to get comfortable around new people but we know with time and patience Potus is going to make a amazing dog because he is already very sweet just very timid.

animal.description:
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 

Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

CARTER WOULD LOVE TO BE IN A FOSTER HOME WHILE HE IS WAITING TO BE ADOPTED. IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN FOSTERING OR ADOPTING CARTER, PLEASE GO TO THE MAKE A DIFFERENCE RESCUE PAGE AND SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE THAT INCLUDES YOUR PHONE NUMBER AND EMAIL ADDRESS.

Carter is a very handsome 2.5 year old Terrier mix. Carter and his brother Benji were living on the streets of Detroit. We were contacted to save them and now they are enjoying a warm place to live, good food and lots of loving. Carter is pretty energetic, goofy and lots of fun!! He loves peanut butter bones and playing with toys. He is working on learning basic commands and is treat motivated. Children 10 years old or older. Carter is good with other dogs after a slow introduction is done. Unfortunately, We do not know how Carter is with cats. His forever home must have a totally enclosed physically fenced yard where he can safely run, play and hang out with his people. Carter is neutered, up to date on his vaccinations, on heart worm preventative as well as house and crate trained. Carter loves to snuggle and adores being petted. Carter cannot wait to share his love with his forever family . . . is that you??

All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. A home visit is required to ensure our dog is going to a safe environment and our dog gets along with your dog(s) and/or cat(s). We require all our dogs over the age of 1 year attend 1 obedience class (6 week session) outside the home. You must live within 1 hour of Birmingham, MI to adopt one of our dogs. No out of state or outside the U.S. adoptions or fosters. Carter's adoption fee is $275.
