animal.description:
Louis-Chihuahua/mixed breed-male-neutered-3 years-Adoption fee: $250 plus tax.   Hello, I’m Louis and I am a 3 year old dog searching for a home! I am looking for a quiet home with one or more adults. Even though I like children, I mostly hide from them because they are too busy and loud for me. I am super quiet myself. I don’t bark and when I talk to you, I offer a very soft whine to let you know I want to go outside or cuddle. I LOVE sitting next to your lap and cuddling in your bed (if you will let me). At night, I like going my own bed - my crate with the door open is my most comfortable space. I sleep all the time, until you want me to cuddle. I won’t bother you while you work (or asleep) and I will follow you around just to be in the same room as you! Right now, I am not big on walks - I don’t like the cold and I am not quite sure how the leash works. My foster family took me on a road trip and I was the perfect car passenger. I hung out in my crate or on a lap. I did really well following the directions in the guest house we stayed at for a few days. I love traveling and will love traveling with my forever adult(s). A few more things about me, it will take me a while to warm up to you. I was quite nervous around my foster family for about a month until I figured out how things went around there. I never bite or show my teeth, I’m a good boy! I am not food motivated and still need to learn a few commands such as sit, stay and come but I know I can learn them (if you want me to). I need eye drops 2-3 times a day (just the over the counter kind) because my tear ducts are permanently blocked. That’s why I have dark circles under my eyes. I originally came from a hoarding situation and was given a second chance at a good life with CCHS. If you’re interested in me, please head to the website to apply.  www.cchswi.org

 I am fixed, current on my rabies, distemper and kennel cough vaccinations. I am heartworm negative(dogs 6 months and older are tested at CCHS) and started on heartworm prevention. I have been de-wormed and I have also been microchipped. I will also be inspected by
a vet and receive a Certificate of Veterinary Inspection. If you are interested in me, please head to the CCHS website at www.cchswi.org and fill out an application. Thank you! DATCP License 266742-DS

animal.description: MEET Bailey! Bailey is a 60lb, 3 year old lab mix. This goofy, playful lady is looking for an adult and teen (15+) only home that is outside of the city, ideally in a more rural or suburban area. While it is not required, she would definitely enjoy having a fenced in back yard. She is looking for an active family who can keep up with all of her energy and who can help her learn that new people and objects are not so scary. Here in the shelter, she has shown us that while she can be friends with other dogs, she would prefer to be an only dog. We do not know how she would be with cats or with other animals. In the right environment, she is a very sweet girl who enjoys getting pets and showing off just how wiggly her bum is! She is very food motivated and while she does known some basic commands such as sit, she would benefit from more positive reinforcement training. If you are looking to add a sweet lady to your family, Bailey may be the girl for you! This animal is currently up to date on all vaccinations, has been spayed, microchipped and been seen by our vet team. If you are interested in adopting this animal, please fill out our web form, available here: Dedham Adoption Inquiry Form! You can expect a response to your inquiry from a member of our adoption staff within 48 hours of completing this form. animal.description:
Velvet hippo alert! Corduroy is a softie, both in body and in personality. He is a big lug who overall seems pretty low-key - though you certainly don't want to count him out for activity! He has a playful, curious streak and enjoys sniffing around on walks. Though he is a strong, sturdy guy, he generally makes for a decent walking companion. And we think he'll be perfectly happy to spend lots of time being a couch potato and snuggle buddy! Corduroy was social with other dogs for his play group assessment. He is estimated to be around 6 years old and weighs 75 lbs.
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 

Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

If you would like an application, please email us.

Bruno's recent adopters have grown to love Bruno but have realized he would be much happier in a home with a fenced in yard, at least one other dog to play with, and a more confident owner.  Although he is getting love, the small townhouse with no yard just doesn't seem big enough for him.  Bruno needs a strong, confident, patient, loving, fun owner.  

A little more about Bruno:
He LOVES to play and he has a lot of energy!   
When done playing, he will cuddle next to you.
He's a great sleeper!  He sleeps through the night.  He will sleep in a crate, but has also been allowed on the bed.  He isn't a crowder.  He does like to sleep in, so don't count on him getting you up for work.  
He has great manners!  He sits for treats and takes them so gently.  He sits for his leash to be put on.  He seeks permission to get on the couch and obeys quickly when told it is time to get off.  He "settles" in his bed when the humans are eating.  He's a gentleman and lets the humans go downstairs first (no tripping).  He often waits going upstairs too, but sometimes he will run ahead.
He is housetrained.
He is sweet!  He gives the appropriate amount of kisses -- you feel loved but aren't left a slobbery mess.
He loves car rides.
He's smart!  Picks up on new commands quickly.  Loves to work puzzles and kongs. 
He is working on walking on a leash. 
We are not sure how he is with kids or cats.

animal.description: Dash is a very sweet boy who just wants to love! He found himself at the shelter because of his previous owner's living situation. He's silly and a bit of an attention hog, but only because he adores affection. His previous owner shared he can be protective when strangers enter the house and doesn't do well when he is around other large dogs. So we are unsure if he is no dogs or dog selective and prefers dogs smaller than him, so a dog meet is a must. He doesn't react to smaller/medium dogs when they walk by him in the shelter, but definitely reacts to larger dogs walking by him. Because of his size and energy we are recommending a home with no young children. A home with teenagers may be fine, so bring them along to the meet. He seems extremely well trained. He really doesn't pull on the lead, knows all basic commands, etc. He loves affection, especially butt scratches. He would do best in a home with a fenced yard or someone who runs, jogs or is active. If you think Dash is a great fit for your family, click on the link to fill out an online application and give the shelter a call to schedule a meet.

Adoption Application: www.wherethewildthingsarerescue.com
Adoption Fee: $300

Gender: Male

Approximate Weight/Size: 75 lbs / Large
Good with: People

Fully Vaccinated: Pending
Neutered/Spayed: Pending
Microchipped: Pending
House Trained: Pending
Crate/Kennel Trained: Yes

Hi I'm Jax, 

I’m a 2 year old pitbull mix, with a big heart and sweet personality. I look like I’m always wearin a tuxedo and the ladies call me a heartbreaker. In the beginning I may not be sure or trust everyone so you have to let me know your trusting and loving  when we first meet. But I am extremely loyal and sweet as you can see from my photos.

I  want affection, love and security from my new family. But it will also be important to have an owner who will help me work through proper training since I didnt get it as a young boy like listening to commands and leash walking properly even when I see other animals. I will require a patient and kind person who is willing to love me as I transform. Once you start training me I am eager to please. Im food and affection motivated which will make it easy on you. 

When we go on walks, In the beginning I pull but I’m learning to slow down with my excitement after a bit.  Riding in Cars make me nervous but I am getting better with that while working with the rescue team. I just dont know what I haven’t learned yet but I’m super smart and pick up on things fast. I don’t like when people just come up to me without proper greeting or go to fast it makes me nervous but the more socialized I get the better I will be at that. I am looking to have a loving, safe and happy life with you as you show me the ropes of the world. 

For now since I wasn’t socialized a lot with other furkids I don’t know how to be around other animals so at the moment I just need to be an only child that way you can focus on my training and we don’t have to share snuggles. With some structure and training I should be able to overcome any hurdle. I would love a beautiful fenced in yard and a bed inside to cuddle with you on.

I promise I’ll be the best decision you made in your life if you pick me!

Adoption Fee: $300
Adoption Application: www.wherethewildthingsarerescue.com

Hi everyone! My name is Lianna. I am a Cane Corso pup approximately 8 months old. Would you like to know my story? It doesn’t start out great like most rescues, but thankfully I know the best life is on its way. You see I am officially a part of WTWTA Rescue and they take loving rescue kids like me and my sisters pretty seriously.  

So, my journey began when my sisters and I were found along a country road dumped off by our previous owners. I know what your thinking, how could somebody abandon beautiful kids like us…sadly this happens more often then it should. My sisters and I decided to stick together while we were off fending for ourselves near the woods. cause that’s what sisters do  We were better as a pack than separated from one another. Thankfully a Good Samaritan who knows mastiffs saw us and picked us up. They were diligent about where we would be placed and who they would allow to rescue us so we could be kept safe and we are grateful for that. 

You see being an italian mastiff breed, we are a pretty “BIG” deal!….see what I did there :P So they contacted WTWTA who knows kids like us well and are specialized in placing our breeds in the right home. Since being a part of WTWTA we are learning what it feels like to be loved again. They took us to get vaccinated. At first i was a little nervous going to the vet’s, but I quickly overcame that and did well in their care. I received all the necessary vaccinations and tests. Sadly, I suffer from a slight heart murmur and something called cherry eye which is to be fixed with surgery covered by the rescue.

I really enjoyed the car ride and the lady who transported me had a big Subaru decked out especially for dogs. There was this huge bed for me in the back to sleep on. I had the whole back bed to myself. It was peaceful and soooooo comfortable I melted like ice cream on a summer day, and while on the way we listened to so many different songs while I slept snuggled in a soft blanket.

After the vet visit, we had a spa day….CAN YOU BELIEVE A SPA DAY!!! I should tell you, during spa day when I had a tubby (bath) I did great, but I was a little scared. However, afterwards, I felt like a million bucks!. They kept commenting on how shiny my coat was. I was shining bright like a black diamond and it felt amazing! I’m sweeter than maple syrup but got some spunk to me too. Throughout this process I learned my favorite thing is when i’m wrapped in human arms and getting love and belly rubs. Now, theres nothing I  want more then to have a person and a family who loves me. Also, Im down if you're up for giving me some self-care (ie. blueberry facials, coconut oil rubs and turkey jerky) I am an Italian gal :) 

At the moment, I am still working on potty training and leash training, so you will have to be patient. I am still coming into who I am, and it may take me a while to completely open up and adjust. I am unsure about other dogs and would need some time and ask my new owners to go slow with me as I learn how to feel safe in the world again. If you currently have another dog, we would need to meet first to ensure we like each other and its a good fit. Right now I am not sure about small animals so no cats or smalls breeds in the home. I would prefer a nice fenced in yard to play in since I am a giant breed and room to run would be perfect! If your wanting a pup with unconditional love then you came to the right place  :)

animal.description:
Mikey is a male, 12lb chi mix who is around 5-6 years old. He came to us as a stray (stray hold has been completed) with a hurt leg and very scared demeanor. It is obvious that Mikey did not see a lot of love and care prior to coming into our rescue, as he has been scared of quick movements and was never housebroken or leash trained. Though he was very scared upon intake, Mikey has made huge strides with his foster family. Mikey seems to be open to affection and has made progress in leash walking and housebreaking (though it still isn't perfect, the belly band is really helping him learn). Someone who adopts Mikey will have to be patient with him and commit to his continued training and housebreaking, also building trust. Mikey has started his vaccinations, is scheduled to be neutered and microchipped, heartworm and lyme disease tested. So far, Mikey is doing great in his foster home with the other dogs and cats. Mikey does not like when other dogs get in his face, so a calmer canine sibling would be ideal. Due to his fears, we would only recommend children over the age of 12 years old, who understand to give him the space that he needs. 
Mikey's adoption fee is $250 which includes his neuter, microchipping, vaccinations and heartworm/lyme testing. If you want to meet Mikey with hopes to make him part of your family, be sure to FIRST apply on our website for approval: https://www.theroadhomeanimalproject.org/companion-adoption-form-pdf.html

*Note: ALL members of the family (canine and human alike) MUST be present for any meet and greet.

Please remember that we are a board of entirely volunteers that have full time jobs as well as our rescue passion. So, be patient with us and check out our Facebook page for more information and photo updates: facebook.com/trhap2014

animal.description:
Lorna is a one year old, Cattle Dog/Great Pyrenees mix with personality traits of both, so experience required. She weighs about 48 pounds. She is ok with other dogs and cats. Kids should be 10+. She knows basic commands, is housebroken, crate trained, and good on leash. She has some resource guarding issues, so she will need someone willing to continue working with her on that. She is highly intelligent and medium energy. She is a very sweet, affectionate girl but will push boundaries. If you are interested in learning more about Lorna, please complete an application and then reach out to Corey@bigfluffydogs.com

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

animal.description:
*We are not hosting adoption events at Petco for the public at this time*
We are currently very busy and have over 100 applications to review and on file. Thank you for your patience! We are working to find everyone a companion. 

Rainy is an adorable 9 week old boxer/lab mix. 

If you are interested in adopting the first step is to fill out an adoption application on our website aaanimalrescue.org. We are currently very busy! Please reach out to allaboardanimalrescue@gmail.com if you have an approved application on file! Please fill out an adoption application on our website if you are ready to adopt! 

Thank you for your patience and understanding during this difficult time! We are on a mission to find everyone companions, we will continue to rescue dogs weekly! We update our page every Monday evening. We are not currently hosting any Petco adoption events for the public. We will be hosting meet/greet adoption appointments!


Breed and size disclosure: As a rescue all of our dogs come to us from high-kill shelters or other rescues, so we do not get a lot of background or information on these dogs. We occasionally receive the mother with the puppies, but in most cases both parents are unknown. Because of this we do not know the full breeding of the dogs. We are required to list the dogs based on the breeds provided to us on their records, but they are all mixed breeds as far as we know, and we cannot guarantee the actual breeds of any of these dogs. Since the full breeding of the dogs is unknown we can also only give you an educated guess on the full-grown size of the dogs. All of the current information we have on the dogs is listed in their bio above. More information may be available at our adoption event, since a lot of the fosters turn in report cards on how the dog has done in their care when they drop them off. 

Adoption Process: If you are interested in adopting from us, the first step of our adoption process is to fill out an application online at http://aaanimalrescue.org/adoption_app.html. It takes us 24-48 hours to process your application and get back to you, via email. Applications turned in Friday afternoon or Saturday morning will not be processed since we are preparing for or at our adoption event. We do have applications on site at our events, but are not always able to approve them at that time and many of the dogs will already have holds on them, so we suggest you fill out an application prior to attending an adoption event. We can place a hold on one dog per approved applicant after a deposit fee has been received, please do not ask to hold a dog if you have not turned in an application and been approved, for the first hour of our adoption event, so that they can get the first chance to meet and hopefully adopt that dog. After the first hour of the event all dogs are available on a first come, first serve basis. If you already have an approved application on file, there will just be more paperwork and the adoption fee at the event, but you will be able to take home the dog/puppy that day. Since we are foster based and do not have a location, our dogs are only available to meet at our events, unless otherwise noted.

animal.description:
*We are not hosting adoption events at Petco for the public at this time*
We are currently very busy and have over 100 applications to review and on file. Thank you for your patience! We are working to find everyone a companion. 

Stormy is an adorable 9 week old boxer/lab mix. 

If you are interested in adopting the first step is to fill out an adoption application on our website aaanimalrescue.org. We are currently very busy! Please reach out to allaboardanimalrescue@gmail.com if you have an approved application on file! Please fill out an adoption application on our website if you are ready to adopt! 

Thank you for your patience and understanding during this difficult time! We are on a mission to find everyone companions, we will continue to rescue dogs weekly! We update our page every Monday evening. We are not currently hosting any Petco adoption events for the public. We will be hosting meet/greet adoption appointments!


Breed and size disclosure: As a rescue all of our dogs come to us from high-kill shelters or other rescues, so we do not get a lot of background or information on these dogs. We occasionally receive the mother with the puppies, but in most cases both parents are unknown. Because of this we do not know the full breeding of the dogs. We are required to list the dogs based on the breeds provided to us on their records, but they are all mixed breeds as far as we know, and we cannot guarantee the actual breeds of any of these dogs. Since the full breeding of the dogs is unknown we can also only give you an educated guess on the full-grown size of the dogs. All of the current information we have on the dogs is listed in their bio above. More information may be available at our adoption event, since a lot of the fosters turn in report cards on how the dog has done in their care when they drop them off. 

Adoption Process: If you are interested in adopting from us, the first step of our adoption process is to fill out an application online at http://aaanimalrescue.org/adoption_app.html. It takes us 24-48 hours to process your application and get back to you, via email. Applications turned in Friday afternoon or Saturday morning will not be processed since we are preparing for or at our adoption event. We do have applications on site at our events, but are not always able to approve them at that time and many of the dogs will already have holds on them, so we suggest you fill out an application prior to attending an adoption event. We can place a hold on one dog per approved applicant after a deposit fee has been received, please do not ask to hold a dog if you have not turned in an application and been approved, for the first hour of our adoption event, so that they can get the first chance to meet and hopefully adopt that dog. After the first hour of the event all dogs are available on a first come, first serve basis. If you already have an approved application on file, there will just be more paperwork and the adoption fee at the event, but you will be able to take home the dog/puppy that day. Since we are foster based and do not have a location, our dogs are only available to meet at our events, unless otherwise noted.

animal.description: Starla is a five-year-old, 33-pound Australian Cattle Dog mix. She was picked up as a stray by a county field officer. Starla was nervous of the officer and they used a snare to contain her. After an initial freak-out, Starla allowed herself to be picked up and carried to the county van. County noted that Starla never attempted to bite any humans; she just stiffened or tried to run. Starla has been slowly gaining her confidence at Home Fur Good. With consistency, routine, and seeing the same employees and volunteers, Starla is expecting certain activities and she is building her trust. She is very alert and watchful; if you talk softly, move slowly, and offer a gentle hand, Starla will seek affection. A few ear scratches and she will be crawling into your lap. County did introduce Starla to a doggie playgroup, but she was fearful around the other dogs. She is working on being brave, and she recently joined the Dog Walking Group. She caught on quickly and relaxed enough to go on a trot and even gave her tail a wag! Although shy, Starla’s curiosity will get the best of her. She will slink her way up to all new people; she is testing it out to see if she can score some loving pets or treats.  Starla will show off her sit and paw skills for a few treats; if you ask her to sit, she does, and immediately hands the paw. She is a sweet girl, a bit cross eyed, but 100% adorable.  Starla would do best in a home of experienced dog owners, ones who understand a fearful dog and are willing to work with Starla and help her to come out of her shell.  She would do best in a home with older children and with low visitor traffic.  Her forever home needs to be able to take new experiences slow.  Starla will need time to decompress in her new home; she will want to understand the rules and routines before being exposed to new scenarios.  An owner with experience in cattle dogs would be very beneficial for Starla.  She is a herding dog and she may try to keep her pack in line. The adoption fee is $225 and includes spaying/neutering, age-appropriate vaccinations, microchipping, and a free wellness visit at Phoenix Mountain Animal Hospital. Our adoption hours are Thursday-Saturday from 11:00 am-4:00 pm by appointment only.

animal.description: Hi, I'm Max! I am an adorable little (about 10 years) old man. I love long naps, soft treats, sitting in the sun on a warm day and a little bit of snuggle time. It doesn't take much to make me happy! I'm pretty quiet, but I can bark now and again. Because I am a senior, I do have some special needs. I'm blind and deaf. I have eye drops for my eyes because I have dry eye and will need to have them every day. I also take a medication for my arthritis and occasional seizures. My foster mom just puts the pill in my food, and I gobble it right up! I will potty outside, but you need to pick me up and carry me outside. I've noticed my foster mom uses that time to sneak in extra hugs and kisses. Even though I am a senior and have a few health issues, I would love the best life possible in my golden years! I am current on all my shots, neutered, microchipped, and heartworm negative. Won't you please consider giving this old guy a chance? XXOO

animal.description:
Adoption Fee: $300
Adoption Application: www.wherethewildthingsarerescue.com

Gender: Female
Breed/s: Cane Corso
Approximate Age: 8 months
Approximate Weight/Size: Current 65 lbs / Giant (Future)
Good with: People and some dogs
Not tested with: Cats and small dogs
Fully Vaccinated: Yes
Neutered/Spayed: Yes
Microchipped: Yes
House Trained: Almost
Crate/Kennel Trained: Yes
Important Notes: Sister to Maya and Lianna

Hi everyone! My name is Sasha. I am an approximately 8 months old Cane Corso. Would you like to know my story? It doesn’t start out great, but I already know I’m going to have the best life. You see I am officially a part of WTWTA Rescue. They take loving us kids pretty seriously.  

So, my journey began when my sisters and I were found along a road. Can you believe we were dumped!! We were fending for ourselves for a while. No matter the circumstances though, my sisters and I decided to stick together.  We were better as a pack than separated from one another. While we were traveling along the road, a Good Samaritan picked us up. They were diligent about where we would be placed and who they would allow rescue us. We are grateful for that. You see we are a pretty BIG deal….see what I did there :P? Well, after their research they contacted WTWTA. Since being a part of WTWTA we are learning what it feels like to be loved. They took us to get vaccinated. I was nervous at the vet’s, but I am strong and know I can overcome anything, and I did. I received shots and had test run to make sure I was healthy. I passed with flying colors.  

Now, I don’t know what everything means. But my driver….yes that’s right! I had a drive because an italian beauty like me should be chauffeured! Let me tell you my driver on my first car trip kept talking and talking. I understood most of the conversation but there was one word i didn’t know…I did not know about this cow-ouch thing... I mean he was telling me how much fun I was going to have when I learned what a cow-ouch and a warm bed was, I dunno I guess ill have to take his word for it… It was a little stressful but he kept telling me how safe I was and how I was a sweet and good pup…. I wasn’t about to argue that comment. What pup would? I know eventually my sisters and I will be separated into loving homes. I was always the protector of my sisters but my rescuer said I didn’t need to be the guardian anymore. Now WTWTA would keep us safe and guard us. I whimpered because I hadn’t known what that felt like in my whole life...  

Now, since being here they have seen some of my personality and traits. I must admit I need a little work,  but with proper training and Love I know I can learn quick and overcome these. I first need to learn to be walked on a leash…..I typically try to walk/drag the hoomans. I cower if you move too quickly or yell, so you will need to be gentle yet confident and firm for me to trust you and feel safe to learn. I do fine with bath time and will sit for my supper if you ask me. At the moment, I have not had a full temperament test done but for now it will be best if I am the only pet in the house until I am further safely socialized. Because of my size and strength I must have a fenced in yard so I can stretch out and run. I’m not done growing so once I am done….I will need room and exercise. I am a guardian breed by nature and although WTWTA say I don’t need to be that anymore…it will come out so I prefer to be with an experienced dog parent that will give me the security I need to know when I need to step in and when I don’t. I am still working on my potty training and that will take some time as I have been kept outside or in a kennel facility so please be patient with me. 

I have been fully vetted and vaccinated and microchipped and passed with flying colors! Now its my time to be with a beautiful family and get the love I've long deserved…

O and my sisters and I agree, now that we are moving up in life we would like weekly blueberry facials rubs and coconut oil spa days :)

If you are interested in Sasha, please list her name on the adoption application.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Name: Ivory
Age: DOB Approx. 1/12/20
Gender: Male
Breed: Pitty
Weight: 71
Dog friendly: Yes
Cat friendly: TBD
Kid friendly: Yes
House Trained: Yes
Crate Trained: Doing well
Energy level: Moderate
History: Pulled from an animal control
Adoption Fee: $500

From the Foster:

Ivory is a loving, playful, and goofy guy who just wants to be around his person as much as possible. He is smart, eager, quick to learn, and loves to please. He has a lot of energy so he would do best in a home with an active lifestyle. Ivory is a strong, compact, muscular and dominant dog that would do best with a person who will be firm, patient, and also provide ongoing training.

Ivory is quick to adapt to new environments and routines. He will go into his crate but requires patience and treats to motivate him. He will protest the first few minutes but is quick to settle himself and relax. I'm currently not crating him and have left him out with my resident dog for 8+ hours a day and have had no issues. He gets along well with other dogs and plays nonstop with my pitbull mix. Although I think he would do fine in a home where he's the only dog, it may be best for him to have a companion to help him gain confidence and teach him how to be a dog.

Ivory is still young and a work in progress. If given the proper training and chance he will make a wonderful companion and loyal sidekick.

animal.description:
Please contact JoEllen (sagdinfo@aol.com) for more information about this pet.Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **
Joy is an adorable 3-month-old Terrier blend. She has a sweet temperament and is active and playful. She will make a loyal companion.
Please understand you are committing to providing a good home for her entire life (up to 15+ years or more) - not just until her puppy cuteness wears off.
You must be committed to housebreaking, age-appropriate enrichment and exercise, leash training, grooming needs, and positive socialization. Like most puppies, she may chew on anything within her reach to include but not limited to baseboards, shoes, socks, children's toys, electrical cords, plants, etc.
Her adoption fee is $250. This includes her spay surgery, rabies vaccination, Nobivac Canine 1-DAPP vaccinations, Bravecto, Drontal Plus, Tri-Heart Plus Chewable Tablet, 24PetWatch microchip, leash and collar, and a trial offer for 24PetWatch Pet Insurance.
Please be aware that puppies and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.
Please ensure your application is complete before submitting. We do verify property ownership, landlord references, apartment/HOA restrictions, veterinary references, and criminal histories.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.
Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@gmail.com.
** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.

Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and opportunity to enroll in a 30-day trial of pet insurance.

Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved and you are traveling from out-of-town, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

Duali (pronounced Dewali) is a 2 year old collie who is a big love bug but scared of his own shadow, all at the same time lol. He lived a pretty sheltered life prior to coming to ODAAT but has been doing great at becoming more social. His way of kissing you is to nose bump you! He loves to play along the fences with the other dogs at the kennel. His Momma, Marcy, also came in with him and he loves playing with her but she bosses him around (like Moms do :)) Duali has made such progress with us and with a family that doesnt mind showing him that the world isnt so scary, we believe he will continue to get better and be an even more wonderful dog! Duali will need another dog companion similar in size in the home as he loves to play and enjoys the company of dogs. If you would like for Duali to join your family please apply through our website
www.onedogatatime.us

BENJI WOULD LOVE TO BE IN A FOSTER HOME WHILE HE IS GETTING HIS HEARTWORM TREATMENT AND WAITING TO BE ADOPTED. IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN FOSTERING OR ADOPTING BENJI, PLEASE GO TO THE MAKE A DIFFERENCE RESCUE PAGE AND SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE THAT INCLUDES YOUR PHONE NUMBER AND EMAIL ADDRESS.

Benji is a very handsome 2.5 year old Terrier mix. Benji and his brother Carter were living on the streets of Detroit. We were contacted to save them and now they are enjoying a warm place to live, good food and lots of loving. He can be a little skittish when meets new people, but quickly warms up to them. Benji is a fun and loving guy. He loves peanut butter, Nylabones and stuffed toys!! He is working on learning basic commands and is treat motivated. Children 10 years old or older. Benji is good with other dogs after a slow introduction is done. Unfortunately, we do not know how Benji is with cats. His forever home must have a totally enclosed physically fenced yard where he can safely run, play and hang out with his people. Benji is neutered, up to date on his vaccinations, on heart worm preventative as well as house and crate trained. Benji cannot wait to be a part of a loving and fun family!!

All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. A home visit is required to ensure our dog is going to a safe environment and our dog gets along with your dog(s) and/or cat(s). We require all our dogs over the age of 1 year attend 1 obedience class (6 week session) outside the home. You must live within 1 hour of Birmingham, MI to adopt one of our dogs. No out of state or outside the U.S. adoptions or fosters. Benji''s adoption fee is $275.

animal.description:
Annie is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet her.

Annie is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~1 year
Weight: ~37lbs
Housebroken: Working on it! She needs to be on a strict schedule. She may also submissive pee out of fear/anxiety.
Crate trained: Working on it! She takes time to settle (10-30 minutes) and would benefit from continued training for this. 
Dog sociability: She has lived with dogs, but is protective over resources (food, space, her person) so would do best as a solo dog in her home. She is friendly while meeting dogs on her walks and has done well in playgroup. She may be a good candidate for daycare as she does enjoy the company of other dogs outside her home.
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Not a match - she resource guards and will do best with adults that understand this behavior
Ideal home: Annie is a sweet gal looking for a home that can help her be her best self! She takes time to settle in new spaces and shows some generalized anxiety. She will do best in adult-only home that is comfortable to read dog body language well and can give her space when needed. 

Little Foster Annie is ready for the sun to come out over her new home! At around one year old, Annie is bursting with energy and loves being active. She becomes instant best friends with every dog she meets and will gladly accept any playdate offered to her! She is still navigating the task of being housebroken, but with a strict schedule, she knows outside is her potty. She loves following you around the home and is happy to snuggle up next to you on the couch for your favorite show at night. She is looking for a patient home that has experience with dogs and dog body language. She doesn't love to be woken up from naps (same, Annie, same!) and she doesn't love her food/bones to be taken away. Respect her boundaries, and her heart will be yours!

Annie's adoption fee is 300. She is up to date on core vaccines, microchipped, spayed and heartworm negative.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description: Wynona Jane is a spayed female 1.5 year old 30lb mixed breed girl - we think she looks like an Australian Shepherd/Spaniel mix. Her name really fits her, since she is small, sweet & full of spunk & energy!! She does know some basic commands, but needs lots of work on her manners. We are currently working on retraining jumping up on people and her mouthiness. Her personality is 100% Aussie/herding dog. She has no off switch and TONS of energy. She loves other dogs and older children, but they must be able to put up with her puppy antics, constant drive for playtime, and high energy level. A home with younger children is not a good fit, since she is fearful of them and doesn't know how to contain her energy yet. Wynona would do best in an active home, preferably with another dog who wants to play with her all the time. She is very timid around new men, but seems to be perfectly fine when meeting new women. We think she could happily live in a home with a man, but they would need to be understanding and respectful of her boundaries. With enough time and positive experiences with men, she should be able to adapt well. Her high food and toy drive make her very easy to train for a dedicated adoptive home! A securely fenced yard is required for Wynona's adoptive home. If you're interested in meeting or adopting Wynona, the first step would be filling out an adoption application via our website scsheltierescue.com. Her adoption donation of $250 includes all vaccinations, spay & microchip. FEBRUARY 2021

animal.description:
~ We kindly ask that you do not ask questions about this dog through Petfinder. Please read our “INTERESTED IN ADOPTING?” section below for guidance. ~

———————------------------

Judy’s a male (yes, male!) Samoyed/Spitz mix is 2 years old and weighs 35 pounds. He was rescued from a dog meat farm along with with his brother Hobbes (from our Wednesday post) and sister Bonnie (who we’ll post soon). He loves going on long walks, has a healthy appetite, and has shown a lot of healthy interest in other dogs. He’s getting more comfortable with toys, and while he loves to carry them around his foster home, he hasn’t yet mastered the art of actually *playing* with them. This smart and adaptive cutie will take some time to open up, but we know that your patience will be rewarded. He’s quick to take in his surroundings, but can get a bit overwhelmed by all of the noises and movements of the big city (we can relate!). If you are a patient adopter in an adults-only home who is ready to help Judy see all of the beauty in his surroundings and grow his independence, we’d love to hear from you!

———————------------------

Our adoption radius is now within 30 miles of the following locations:  NYC, Philadelphia, Lehigh Valley, DC, Baltimore, MD, and Western & Eastern CT. You must be able to pick up the dog at our office in Astoria, Queens (no exceptions). You must wear a mask and practice safe social distancing when traveling and picking up the dog.

———————------------------

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING?

Please check our Adopt page (www.koreank9rescue.org/adopt) and our Adoption FAQ (www.koreank9rescue.org/adoption-faq) to learn more! These pages include our requirements, adoption fees, adoption procedures, currently adoptable dogs, answers to frequently asked questions, and the link to our online adoption application!


NOT READY TO ADOPT BUT LOVE OUR DOGS?


As a 501(c)(3) dog rescue, we rely on donations to continue saving these precious dogs. Check our Donate page (www.koreank9rescue.org/donate) and our Patreon (www.patreon.com/koreank9rescue) to help support our rescue. Let's keep making a difference together!

animal.description:
Meet Trike! 

Trike is about 4 years old, male neutered, terrier mix. He is SOO friendly, playful, and active. Trike cannot wait to learn manners, leash skills, and obedience with his new hooman.

Trike had been hit by a car and due to this has a limp (no broken bones, hurray!) - which is healing under a local vet's supervision. This injury can take at least 6 months to heal, and he may have a limp forever. But he was cleared to find his furever home now!

With the history of being hit by a car, a fenced in yard is preferred. Trike would love a home with an active lifestyle, his leg does not slow him down at all! Kids 10 years and up would be best as he is very playful. He would possibly like a spayed/neutered playmate.

This boy would be an awesome companion!

animal.description:
Age: 10 mos. 
Weight: 65.6  lbs.
Good with dogs: Yes
Good with cats:  Untested
Good with kids:  Yes
Energy Level: High/Medium
Available for Adoption: 1/6/2021 (Currently accepting applications).
Applications need to be approved before a meet and greet will be set up for any Fetching Hearts Rescue dogs. 

Meet Hena! Hena is a 10 month old, 65lbs. Sweetheart.  She has an unusual spotted/brindle coat with interesting markings. Hena aims to please her people and makes her foster chuckle with her goofy, somewhat clumsy antics. This girl loves squeaky toys and plays a great game of fetch. She does well with other dogs and kids, but has not had the opportunity to meet any cats yet. Hena is still working on her crate, leash, and house training. She has made great strides so far, but is looking forward to working on her training with her future family. Hena is ready for a family that can provide her with a long life full of love and joy! Don't miss out on this sweetheart.

If interested in Hena, please email to inquire at: SCREENING.FETCHINGHEARTS@GMAIL.COM OR COPY LINK BELOW TO APPLY AND FILL OUT AN APPLICATION: https://www.fetchingheartsrescue.org/adoption-form-online
to fill out an application.

Unless otherwise indicated, all dogs adopted through Fetching Hearts have received the following before being available for adoption:

Thorough veterinary examination.

All routine annual vaccinations, including Rabies, DHLPP, Bordatella (Kennel Cough), Heartworm Test, Fecal Test, Deworming, Microchip, Flea and Tick Prevention and Heartworm Prevention.

Spay/Neuter.
All dogs are quarantined for two weeks outside of the shelter (puppies four weeks) to ensure they don't break with disease.

VETTING NOTE: Fetching Hearts Rescue completely vets our dogs thoroughly to the best of our knowledge based on communication with our Southern Vets. If anything is brought to our attention, we treat the dog. After adopting the dog, you will be responsible for following up with all vetting going forward.

HEARTWORM NOTE: Dogs who were treated for Heartworm can test positive up to 4-6 months after last treatment. All dogs are immediately put on Heartguard/Ivermectin following the treatment to kill the Heartworm larvae. All dogs should be re-tested after 5-6 months from the last Heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
Hi my name is Emmett. I am a Great Pyrenees mix. Maybe mixed with Lab? And aren't I just so handsome? My owner surrendered me because she was commuting for school and no longer able to give me the care and attention I deserve. I was an outside dog before I came to rescue, but I have learned that I like to be inside with my people and 4 legged friends. My new owners will need to have a little patience with me to get over my shyness, but once I do I will show you my personality! I really need another canine friend in my new home and I also like cats. I am working on leash training and prefer quiet walks, avoiding busy roads because I'm not used to all the noises. Some of my favorite things are toys that crinkle, bacon cheese dog biscuits, and lounging on my foster mom's bed. I also like to snuggle! I am house trained, have mastered sit, and am working on other commands. I will come to you neutered, up to date on vaccinations, up to date on flea/tick preventives, and microchipped. 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved you must pass a home check and a vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. I can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, Wisconsin, Indiana, and Michigan. My rescue is able to transport me to those states. If you would like to give me a furever home, please fill out an application on my rescue's website. 

Being fostered in Bradley, IL

animal.description:
BELLA IS IN A FOSTER HOME

Date of birth:  11/2016

1/26/2021:  Bella is an adorable little Beagle/American Staffordshire mix!  She’s  4 years old and weighs 35 lbs— she’s a nice size.  

•  Bella is extremely sweet natured.  The poor girl has had a rough life. She was living on the streets with her puppies. She’d belonged to somebody at some time, though, and was neglected— she had multiple collars that had become embedded into her neck. She was so patient while we removed them from her neck. 

• Bella is doing great in her foster home. She is playful and loves to play fetch.  She’s very food motivated and she can catch treats in her mouth when you toss them to her!

• Bella is sometimes a little shy with new people, so it may take her a bit to warm up when you initially meet her.  But once she’s comfortable she’s very loving and she loves attention. 

• We don’t want to place her in a home with young kids.  We think she’d be fine with teenagers who’ve been raised with dogs and know to be respectful while she adjusts to her new home.  

• We’d like Bella to have a house with a fenced yard for her to play in.

• Bella gets along well with other dogs and lives with other dogs in her foster home.  If you have a dog, we’d ask you to bring your dog in to meet Bella to see if they could be buddies. 

• Bella is crate trained and house trained. She uses a doggie door in her foster home.

• She’s been spayed, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heartrworms.  She is such a sweetheart and she’s endured a hard life. She’s ready for a home where she’ll get lots of love and attention! 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE:  PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU.  Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info. 

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:
Email: christine@hsgkc.org
Phone: 913.521.2339
hsgkc.org

animal.description: Logan is a 1-2 year old Pit bull mix. He is loose and wiggly. He comes when called and will stay next to his person. He likes to give gentle chin nudges. Logan will lean for attention. He is high energy so this guy will need plenty of playtime and exercise! He pulls on a leash but with some basic obedience training, this could easily be resolved. He is food motivated and knows the sit command. He is not a fan of cats in a shelter environment. Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Our cat test should be used as a general purpose screening only to rule out overt aggression; we always recommend caution when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; JHS believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. Always remember that the majority of dogs at our shelter have been exposed to or may have kennel cough. Kennel cough is contagious to other dogs, please talk to your vet if you have any questions about kennel cough prior to adoption. Please ask your adoption counselor at time of adoption if you have any unanswered questions regarding illnesses and treatments of the path that you are adopting. For more information about this dog or any others at our Shelter, please visit www.joplinhumane.org. We are the Joplin Humane Society in Joplin, Missouri. 417-623-3642

animal.description:
Meet Mortimer, a two year old Basset Hound and Catahoula mix. He weighs approximately 45 to 50 pounds. Sweet Morty has never met a stranger and is always happy. Morty came into rescue during heartworm treatment and is finally healthy and ready to find his perfect home. Morty had to be on exercise restrictions due to his heartworm treatment and has flourished since being able to run and play with other dogs after completing treatment. He is high energy but will settle down and watch television with you at night. He would love a family that is active or a high energy doggie sibling to help him use his energy. He annoys his low energy (senior citizen) foster brother as well as his small foster brother (20 pounds) because he is very "touchy feely" but he loves to run and play with his 80 and 50 pound foster dog brothers. Morty is confined to a small room when his foster mom isn't home. He will howl for a few minutes but settles down well.  Morty is potty trained. He does not live with children but he is super friendly with everyone he meets on walks. Since he likes to jump, he would probably do well in a family without children or with older children in case he jumps. Morty has never met a toy he didn't like, or a treat! Mortimer has a cat foster sister and he is overzealous but not aggressive. He will stop chasing her with the "no" command.  Morty clearly had a rough start to life but he is ready to find his perfect ending and he hopes that is you. Morty's adoption fee is $250. 

To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

Spracket
~2 year old, male
Beagle Mix
Welcome Spracket! He arrived from Idaho Falls last week and has been decompressing in his wonderful foster home while we got him on the right track. As you can see, his skin is not in the greatest condition. Although his previous owner loved him dearly they could not accommodate his special diet needs so they did what was best for him to get him where he needed to be to find the right home. We suspect he has severe food allergies and will need to be a Hydrolyzed Protein diet. We are working closely with the team at Jackson Animal Hospital to get him on the right track! He has done well with all cats and dogs so far and is gaining his confidence with meeting new people!

Please note, Animal Adoption Center cannot guarantee the breed, composition or ages of our dogs as we usually have no history prior to them entering the rescue. We make every effort to ensure the dogs are healthy.

Please know that our intention is to insure long lasting committed homes for the animals at the AAC. If we feel that an animal and a potential owner are not a good fit we reserve the right to refuse adoption.

Meet James, a 1-2 year old, male, Cattle Dog mix who is lovely! He has been with us for a few weeks but we had to address an injured hip before he was up to adoption! He received a femoral head ostectomy at Jackson Animal Hospital and is ready to find a forever home. He has done well with dogs and kids and will need someone that can help him finish his rehab!

A note from his foster: "He will do ANYTHING for a belly rub or treat and loves puzzle toys. Lives to please his person. Very smart and learning basic commands very quickly. Housebroken and now crate trained and uses a doggy door. He has a shoe fetish and likes to relocate them to enhance your morning with a nice 6am scavenger hunt. A little reserved with new dogs at first if they're too rambunctious but enjoys wrestling and playing keep-away with the playful ones. Overall he's a big puppy, can be a little mouthy (just like a puppy, not mean) but is learning quickly with consistency. Oh and a huge comfort hound! You can always count on him to find the most luxurious bed in the house and claim his spot for a good snooze!"

animal.description:
Double Dot is a petite little girl with adorable cow spots and a BIG personality. She arrived to RACC as a stray with no known history, but it took her no time at all to let that fun personality shine! Dot has been a volunteer favorite, as she walks nicely on leash and loves to play in the yard between giving you kisses. Double Dot has a wild play style and is jumpy and excitable (she means well!), so a home with young children may not be best for her. This play style is also similar with other dogs, but she may be able to go home with another dog who can tolerate her shenanigans! Dot thrives when she has stimulation and exercise, so she's hoping her next human will take her hiking or on other outdoor adventures. That said, she is not an ideal apartment dog and will do much better in a home with a yard where she can run. If you're looking for an adventure partner rather than a couch potato, ask to meet with Dot!

animal.description:
Hunk ACCT-A-82311
Intake: Owner/Guardian Surrender (Aggression to Animals)
Age: 9M
Sex: Male
Altered: No

Medical Observation:
1/21 (Vet Check) --The patient is an apparently healthy dog. No skin issues were appreciated, and his neuter site appears healthy. No treatment is needed. 
1/17 (Intake Exam) -- Red; irritated eyes. Testicles look very red and irritated.
1/8 (Intake Exam) -- Eyes - irritation/abrasion around eyes. Ears - small abrasions in ears. Mouth/Teeth/Gums - irritation/abrasion around mouth

Behavior Observation: 
1/29 (Per Staff) -- Please be cautious when taking out and returning to kennel. Dog is highly kennel reactive, he will escalate when being returned and it could lead to a bite. 
1/26 (Per Staff) Approached kennel, and was easily able to remove Ace. Greeted at the door loose and wiggly. Pulled moderately on leash. Continued to check in with handler. Became overstimulated after a few minutes outside and started to hump and then leash bite. Ace continued to pull at the leash, and attention could not be redirect until another staff member called him over. Returned to walking on the leash, but started to leash bite/ tug on the leash when being returned to kennel. Handler stepped into kennel and ace followed allowing to be returned to kennel.
1/21 (Per Vet) -- Friendly and easy to handle for exam. Attempted to nip when being placed back into kennel (also observed in adoptive home)
1/17 (Per Vet) -- Friendly; BAR
1/9 (Per Volunteer) Kennel Presentation - Easy to leash/social. Does not want to return to kennel. Leash Skills - Pulls Strongly On Leash. Handleability - Loose/Allows all handling. Humper but then becomes a hugger. Will stay attached if handler allows humping to continue. Engages in tag. Gives toys up willingly. Evaluated Blue.
1/8 (Per Vet) BAR; FRIENDLY
1/8 (Per APO) The dog is in the house on his cage. I put my stick on his neck and he scare but never aggressive with us .
1/8 (Per Previous Owner) attacked and killed her cat and is now acting aggressively towards her when she tries to feed him. he lived in the home with two chihuahua and two cats and got along well with them for 10 months - according to owner Cerberus was playing with one of the chihuahua and the cat ran past them and Cerberus attacked the cat and killed it - the owner put Cerberus in the cage but when she went to go feed him his behavior seemed as if he would bite her. owner stated he just likes to chase children so she usually puts him away in another room when kids are around but usually Cerberus is allowed to roam freely in the home. Owner stated his behavior around adults and said that he is very hyperactive but friendly and likes to jump on people which people usually do not like and sometimes get scared but he has no bite history with people.

BITE DETAILS
1/16 - Adopter reported to me that they had just gotten home from adopting Ace, he was on a leash and Mr Valdez went to put Ace in the crate but instead Ace turned around and bit the owner on the arm and the finger. Did not break skin, did not cause bleeding but did leave a scratch mark. Mr Valdez stated to me that he knows Ace is a good dog and he can probably work with Ace but his girlfriend is now scared of the dog and does not want him 
1/16 - While being returned to kennel by a volunteer, he began leash biting and refusing to return to kennel. Approached by staff member to assist, and Cerberus, clearly overstimulated/overwhelmed with flailing body, redirected and nipped at staff member's leg through jeans. Did not break skin. Staff then went to other side of kennel, opened door, and encouraged dog to step back into kennel via the other side. Volunteer was then able to close door behind, leaving leash on. When volunteer attempted to open door back up to retrieve leash, dog then began pushing to get of kennel again. During this time, dog again became mouthy, jumping up on volunteer and nipped at hands, drawing a small amount of blood. Leash was removed, however, door was shut carefully. Band-aid used to cover finger. Dog remained over-stimulated but friendly.

animal.description:
Lindy came from an overcrowded shelter in Arkansas. She’s a sweet girl who loves to play with her resident dog outside. Tug of war is a favorite game. Has not  barked. Very good in the kennel, hasn't messed it and sleeps through the night. Hasn't noticed the cats but loves the resident human boys. Always moving when not sleeping. Would love a fenced yard or play time at the dog park!

Adoption Fee: $450 (cash/card only) 

Foster to call: Jennifer 952-431-9910

Due to the recommendations about the coronavirus, we are not able to have group adoption events at PetSmart.  We are, however, allowed to do individual adoptions so if you are interested in this pup/dog, please contact the foster listed above to set up a meeting.  We look forward to continuing to save dogs with you and will resume group adoptions as soon as we can.  Thank you for your patience and understanding.

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home.  An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home.  Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home & truly become comfortable.  There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption; discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, & 3 months.  We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.   

Last Hope, Inc. is an all volunteer, foster based, no kill rescue! You can see almost all of our dogs on Saturdays from 11am - 3pm at Lakeville PetSmart (located by Hy-Vee just off 160th & Pilot Knob) & Burnsville Petsmart (located just off Hwy 35E & County Rd 42 by Chianti Grill).

Policies: You do not have to have a fence to adopt a dog from us, but some dogs will require a fence or acres to play, or an active family who will make sure the dog gets the exercise it needs to be happy.  Some dogs do not have the temperament that will do well with young children.   

The Adoption Fee is not enough to cover the vet bills. Sales tax of almost 7.25% is also included in the adoption fee that you see. Please consider donating to Last Hope to help us save these animals!

CAN YOU FOSTER? By taking a dog or puppies temporarily into your home and then coming to our adoption days to help find them homes, we can save more! If you’re interested, please email our dog coordinator: jaime3369@gmail.com and give us your contact information and what you would like to foster and someone will get back to you! You can also apply to be a foster home on our webpage! In the upper left hand corner there’s a drop down tab with the link for canine foster home. Just fill it out online & submit! We will get back to you as quick as we can.

It was hard to pry BRANDY away from Miss Donna and volunteer Jordan, but we did end up capturing some pictures of this big, beautiful girl on a brisk winter morning in the hopes that an adopter finds her as wonderful as many of the staff and volunteers.

animal.description: ANNIE is a middle aged lab/pit mix.   She ended up in the shelter and when the owner was called they told the shelter they didnt want her anymore.   ANNIE had had her fair share of  puppies and perhaps was no longer useful in that department.  ANNIE is a graduate of our Paws Behind Bars prison dog program where she did very well and now knows basic obedience.   From the prison she went to a great foster home with a young couple in an apartment  (so we know she can handle that lifestyle)   Her likes?   PEOPLE and PEANUT BUTTER!   Her dislikes?   She doesnt like to be left alone and while she'll tolerate other dogs she likes them better from afar.   She is a lovely companion,  that is a great walking partner.   Her energy level is perfect for someone wanting a quieter dog.   If interested in adopting,  our process begins with the application which you can find at www.adoptmebluegrasspetrescue.

animal.description:
**Hello! Derek is currently staying in a foster home. If you'd like to schedule a time to meet him please call Wayside's Adoption Center at 816-986-4426. Thanks!**
Hi there, Im Derek! Im friendly and affectionate and silly and fun. There is no place on this earth Id rather be than right by your side, basking in the feeling of closeness as you pet me and tell me about your day. Ill even climb up on your lap, if you let me! Despite my big stature, sometimes Im just a little lap dog in my mind. Ha! Ill be your constant companion if you just give me a chance.
Im a handsome, 8 year old, 69-pound sweetheart with an adorable furrowed brow and a delightful personality. And I think Im already mostly housebroken, but please stay patient with me when we get home, as I get used to my new routine with you. I first came to Wayside as a stray when I was only a year old. I was adopted, but then ended up as a stray once again. Life can be tough out there on your own, especially for a dog that loves people as much as I do. What I really want is to share my life with you and to be your family. I might be a senior, but I have so very much love left to give.
Maybe because of all the instability Ive had in my life, I can be a little shy and nervous when first meeting new people. I warm up quickly though and, once we bond, I like to lean into you to show you my love and affection. With time, I become a playful, happy, outgoing dog who loves to play with my toys and balls. Im an expert at the game of fetch! Im big and strong, so when I joyfully jump around, I can be like a bull in a china shop. Good thing Im smart and easy to redirect when I get too rowdy! I already know all sorts of commands that I cant wait to show you and Id love to learn more. I hope youll continue my training throughout my life. I will thrive if you stay patient, calm, positive, and consistent with me. I love tasty treats and praise, so just let me know when Im a good boy and Ill be all over it! 
Now that Ive been at the shelter for a while, I get chosen to do fun stuff with the staff and volunteers. I love to go for field trips! Im content when riding in the car. And Im friendly and social with everyone I meet when Im out and about. I even let kids pet me. I love belly rubs and I soak up the attention of all my new friends. I have a gentle, easy-going temperament. I also get to be an office foster dog on occasion, meaning I help the staff with their work throughout the day. Im well behaved and a nice friend to spend your day with. I mostly like to nap on the couch or cuddle, but other times I try to get my friends to take a break from their work to pet me. Im also good at keeping myself entertained with toys. I do have a loud bark when I have something to say! I cant wait until the day when I get adopted and I get to go to a real home!
I love to go for walks and I do pretty well on my leash. I am strong though, so a harness helps to keep me from pulling. I like to focus on our time together during my walks and I dont like to meet other dogs along the way. I will need a home as your only dog and I dont want to spend time in dog parks or doggy daycare or whatnot. I just need to be your one and only friend, but I promise Ill give you so much love and attention that I will be enough!
Im just a simple dog who has never had much in life. I long for a peaceful, safe, stable life with people I love. I want to share my life with you and be there for you whenever you need me. I will be your best friend and Ill show you how it feels to be loved unconditionally. Im an expert at that! Please come to meet me soon!
Love, Derek
 ...

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21

animal.description:
Meet Maggie, our 5 1/2 year old Beagle/Terrier mix girl! Maggie is about 25lbs and the sweetest little thing! She is looking to put the shelter life behind her as soon as possible so she can rest comfortably in the warmth of her very own forever home. Maggie likes the company of others and enjoys lounging in a lap. She doesn't seem to mind the company of her kennelmates either.

To view the adoptable dogs at our shelter, you must fill out an adoption application found on our website. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, we are showing dogs on an appointment only basis. Please understand that we are receiving a high volume of applications at this time and are doing our best to address as many as we can. Please be patient. Thank you.

The adoption fee for adult dogs is $250. Aside from the shelter, food and water, exercise and compassion they receive while in our care, this also includes veterinary services such as Rabies, Distemper+Lepto, Bordetella, H3N2/H3N8 Influenza, heartworm testing, fecal exams, preventions and deworming medications. Spays/Neuters are also included as part of the adoption fee as is microchipping. 
Puppies under the age of 6 months have an adoption fee of $350. The veterinary services rendered include puppies first round of vaccines, fecal exams, deworming medications, preventions, and microchipping. Our facility spays and neuters dogs at 6 months of age. If the puppy is adopted prior to his, or her prescheduled surgery date, a $200 spay/neuter deposit will be taken on the day of adoption. This deposit it refundable and will be returned to the adopter once proof of the procedure is returned to the shelter. 
COVID-19 NOTE: Please understand that we are looking for forever home for our pets. We understand that many people have a lot of time on their hands during the COVID-19 pandemic, so this may seem like an ideal time to bring home a new pet. Please be sure you are prepared to give your new pet his, or her forever home once our lives go back to normal. They deserve it. Thank you and stay safe.

animal.description:
Johnny Cash NM 1 1/2 -2ish? Bordercollie X
Shy Dog

Best Home Fit:
- Single family home ( no apartment)
- Someone committed to continue his confidence journey 
- A home with other calm older dogs to mentor him
- A fenced yard ( but getting good on leash as well)

Strengths:
- Gets along with all dogs
-Gets along with cats
- A very sweet temperament

Developing:
- Leash walking
- being confident around new people ( but the power of cheese goes a long way)

He Walks the Line

Johnny is one of the very last dogs to come from the July hoarding case where we and a number of other rescues pulled and rehomes 40+ dogs.
Other dogs that came from that rescue were:
( Reba, Shania, Trisha,etc. ) 

This amazing sweet soul is the very last to finally get sprung from boarding jail. We have been working on finishing up his confidence building here and have found he is just a star!
He is so ready to find love and write his soul searing memoir of his journey thus far.

He will need a bit more guidance but boy is he ready to dig in and take root in his forever family. 

Could you be the one to take this man in black to erased all his Hurt and help him find his new day??
